{"title_page": "Jeff Ross", "text_new": "{{short description|American stand-up comedian, insult comic, actor, and director}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name = Jeff Ross\n| image = Jeff Ross, Joint Base Andrews, May 2016 (cropped).jpg\n| caption =  Ross in May 2016\n| birth_name = Jeffrey Ross Lifschultz\n| pseudonym = Roastmaster General\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1965|9|13}}\n| birth_place = <!-- PLEASE NOTE: Any addition to this field without a properly cited reference will be reverted. If you need help, please post an edit request to the article's talk page -->\n| medium = [[Stand-up]], [[television]], [[film]], [[books]]\n| active = 1994\u2013present\n|height  = 1.79 m\n| genre = [[Insult comedy]], [[observational comedy]], [[black comedy]], [[cringe comedy]], [[satire]]\n| subject = [[Jewish culture]], [[popular culture]], [[self-deprecation]], [[sex]], [[current events]], [[religion]]\n| notable_work = [[Comedy Central Roasts]]<br/>''[[Patriot Act: A Jeffrey Ross Home Movie]]''<br/>''[[The Burn with Jeff Ross]]''\n}}\n'''Jeffrey Ross Lifschultz''' (born September 13, 1965),<ref name=HAARETZ>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 13, 2018 |title=Jewish Insider's Daily Kickoff: September 13, 2018 - Birthdays |url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/jewish-insider-s-daily-kickoff-september-13-2018-1.6470421 |work=[[Haaretz]] |location=Tel Aviv, Israel |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=Comedian who earned the title \"Roastmaster General\" for his [[insult comedy]] and Comedy Central celebrity roasts, Jeff Ross (born Jeffrey Ross Lifschultz) turns 53...}}</ref> known professionally as '''Jeff Ross''', is an American stand-up comedian, writer, director and actor. He is also known as the \"'''Roastmaster General'''\" for his [[insult comedy]] and his multiple appearances at celebrity [[Roast (comedy)|roasts]] held by the [[New York Friars Club]] and on the ''[[Comedy Central Roast]]'' television series.<ref name=NPR>{{Cite episode |title=Having Thick Skin Is A 'Survival Technique,' Says Comic Jeff Ross |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/13/493688206/having-thick-skin-is-a-survival-technique-says-comic-jeff-ross |access-date=May 1, 2019 |series=Fresh Air |series-link=Fresh Air |first=Gross |last=Terry |network=NPR |date=September 13, 2016 |time=0:30 |quote=...but he's best known for the Comedy Central celebrity roasts; he's one of the producers and has been a roaster on each one since 2005.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Zinoman |first=Jason |date=July 29, 2016 |title=Insult Comedy as Blood Sport: The Rise of the Roast Battle |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/30/arts/television/insult-comedy-as-blood-sport-the-rise-of-the-roast-battle.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=When Mr. Ross, who had become known as the Roastmaster General because of his performances on Comedy Central\u2019s celebrity events...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pilot |first=Jessica |date=November 7, 2014 |title=The Roast Battle: \u2018Like Fight Club for Comedians,\u2019 Says Jeffrey Ross |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2014/11/07/the-roast-battle-like-fight-club-for-comedians-says-jeffrey-ross/ |work=[[The Village Voice]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=Today, Jeff Ross is practically a household name. He has been the Roastmaster at the venerable Friars Club, and is part of every Comedy Central Roast...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Brownstein |first=Bill |date=July 9, 2011 |title=Just for Laughs 2011: Roastmaster Jeffrey Ross has a serious side |url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/just+laughs+2011+roastmaster+jeffrey+ross+serious+side/5073993/story.html |work=[[Montreal Gazette]] |location=Montreal, Quebec, Canada |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=Ross is the current New York Friars\u2019 Club Roastmaster General and a regular on the Comedy Central Roasts.}}</ref> In 2009 the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' called Ross \"the new millennium [[Don Rickles]].\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Steve |date=October 13, 2009 |title=Mr. Cruel |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2009-10-13-0910130087-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, Illinois, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=He got to this place, as the new millennium Don Rickles, partly thanks to an insult-loving uncle, partly as a result of working in his dad's New Jersey catering business, where a multicultural work crew loved to bust on the boss' son.}}</ref> His directorial debut, the 2006 documentary ''[[Patriot Act: A Jeffrey Ross Home Movie]]'', won the prize for Best Film at the [[Comedia (festival)|Comedia film festival]] held at the [[Just for Laughs]] comedy festival in [[Montreal]].<ref name=VARIETY2>{{cite magazine |last=Adalian |first=Josef |date=October 20, 2004 |title=Ross roasts lead to toast from Fox |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/comedy-central-jeff-ross-roast-battle-1201909718/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |location=Los Angeles, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=PASTEPATRIOT>{{cite magazine |last=Zaino III |first=Nick A. |date=September 28, 2005 |title=Comedia: Laughing Stock of Film Festivals |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2005/09/comedia-laughing-stock-of-film-festivals.html |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |location=Decatur, Georgia, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRoss was raised in [[Newark, New Jersey]], until he was in second grade; then his family moved to [[Union, New Jersey]]{{dn|date=October 2019}}, and later to [[Springfield Township, Union County, New Jersey|Springfield, New Jersey]], where he attended [[Jonathan Dayton High School]].<ref name=NJ>{{cite news |last=Considine |first=Bob |date=September 29, 2011 |title=Take 5 with Jeffrey Ross |url=https://www.nj.com/inside-jersey/2011/09/take_5_with_jeffrey_ross.html|archivedate=May 2, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190502051415/https://www.nj.com/inside-jersey/2011/09/take_5_with_jeffrey_ross.html|url-status=live|work=[[The Star-Ledger]] |location=Newark, New Jersey, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=I grew up in Newark, Union and Springfield. ... So we lived in Newark until I was in second grade, then we jumped to Union and then to Springfield, where I kind of stayed for a while. I lost my Mom when I was 14 and my Dad when I was 19...}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url= https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/I-Only-Roast-the-Ones-I-Love/Jeffrey-Ross/9781439102794 |title=I Only Roast the Ones I Love: Busting Balls Without Burning Bridges|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|page=64 |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=It wasn't until I reached Jonathan Dayton Regional High School in Springfield that I discovered the great power of the put-down.}}</ref> He is of [[Jewish]] heritage and has a younger sister named Robyn.<ref name=HAARETZ/><ref name=ISRAEL>{{cite news |last=Wootliff |first=Raoul |date=January 10, 2018 |title=Chris Rock bares soul in roaringly honest Israel debut |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/chris-rock-bares-soul-in-roaringly-honest-israel-debut/ |work= |location= |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=Veteran roaster Jeff Ross..repeatedly told the audience of his Jewish roots, noting, \u201cI love my people and you are my people...\u201d }}</ref><ref name=PLAYBOY>{{cite magazine |last=Buckland |first=Jason |date=January 27, 2017 |title=Roastmaster General Jeffrey Ross Stands Up for More than Comedy |url=http://www.playboy.com/articles/jeff-ross-profile |url-status=live |magazine=[[Playboy]] |location=Chicago, Illinois, United States |publisher=Playboy Enterprises |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313135521/http://www.playboy.com/articles/jeff-ross-profile |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> His mother Marsha died from [[leukemia]] when he was 14 years old.<ref name=NJ/><ref name=PLAYBOY/><ref name=NPRPARENTS>{{Cite episode |title=Having Thick Skin Is A 'Survival Technique,' Says Comic Jeff Ross | url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/13/493688206/having-thick-skin-is-a-survival-technique-says-comic-jeff-ross |access-date=April 21, 2019 |series=Fresh Air |series-link=Fresh Air |first=Gross |last=Terry |network=NPR |date=September 13, 2016 |time=29:05 |quote=Terry Gross: \"So you mention your parents. Your mother died when you were 14. Did she have cancer?\" Jeff Ross: \"She had leukemia.\" TG: \"Then your father died when you were 19; that was sudden and unexpected.\" JR: \"Yeah, doin' stupid stuff. Drugs.\" TG: \"Oh really?\" JR: \"He was a single guy starting to make money in the 80s. I was away at college, my sister was a senior in highschool.\"}}</ref> His father died of drug-related causes when Ross was 19 years old\u2014Ross was attending college at the time and his sister was a [[Senior (education)|senior]] in high school.<ref name=NJ/><ref name=NPRPARENTS/> His father owned and ran Clinton Manor Catering, a [[catering]] business that was started by Ross's great-grandmother.<ref name=NPRCLINTON>{{Cite episode |title=Having Thick Skin Is A 'Survival Technique,' Says Comic Jeff Ross |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/13/493688206/having-thick-skin-is-a-survival-technique-says-comic-jeff-ross |access-date=April 21, 2019 |series=Fresh Air |series-link=Fresh Air |first=Gross |last=Terry |network=NPR |date=September 13, 2016 |time=27:23 |quote=My great grandmother Rose, she started it a long time ago in the 50s...It was in Newark, New Jersey, and then later in Union, New Jersey. It was called Clinton Manor Catering. Judy Bloom wrote about it in her book \"Wifey\".}}</ref>  The business was located in [[Newark, New Jersey]], and later moved to [[Union, New Jersey]].{{dn|date=October 2019}}<ref name=NPRCLINTON/>\n\nRoss attended [[Boston University]] as a [[broadcasting]] and [[film]] [[Major (academic)|major]] with a [[Minor (academic)|minor]] in [[political science]].<ref name=SANLUIS>{{cite news |last=Pemberton |first=Patrick S. |date=October 2, 2014 |title=Roastmaster General: Comedian Jeff Ross on the art of the roast |url=https://www.sanluisobispo.com/entertainment/arts-culture/article39498495.html |work=[[The Tribune (San Luis Obispo)|The Tribune]] |location=San Luis Obispo County, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=After losing both parents while in his teens, the New Jersey native studied communications at Boston University...}}</ref> <ref name=CAPECOD>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Jim |date=July 31, 2017 |title=Jeff Ross: Roastmaster General |url=https://www.capecodtimes.com/entertainmentlife/20170731/jeff-ross-roastmaster-general |work=[[Cape Cod Times]] |location=Hyannis, Massachusetts, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> He graduated from the [[Boston University College of Communication]] in 1987.<ref name=CAPECOD/> Ross also worked as the music director at the university's student-run radio station [[WTBU (Boston University)|WTBU]] in addition to working for the university's [[public radio]] station [[WBUR]] where he worked as an [[audio engineer]].<ref name=CAPECOD/>\n\nRoss credits his tough upbringing in New Jersey for helping him develop his talent for insult comedy, which he says he developed as a defense mechanism.<ref name=CHICAGOTRIB>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Steve |date=October 13, 2009 |title=Mr. Cruel |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2009-10-13-0910130087-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, Illinois, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=ATLANTA>{{cite news |last=Ho |first=Rodney |date=July 18, 2014 |title='Roastmaster General' born to insult |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/423299230/ |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |location=Dunwoody, Georgia, United States |page=D4 |access-date=May 1, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com ||url-access=subscription|quote=Ross said his ability to insult people goes back to childhood in New Jersey. 'Everyone in my family was good at it. I had to quickly learn not just to take a joke but to give it back. My uncle Murray was the first to bust my chops. We called him mean Murray. He'd make fun of my braces, my buck teeth. I worked at my parent's catering hall and was the boss' son.  He would give me a lot of crap.'}}</ref> Ross stated in an interview with ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'': \"Everyone in my family was good at [roasting]. I had to quickly learn not just to take a joke but to give it back. My uncle Murray was the first to bust my chops. We called him mean Murray.\"<ref name=ATLANTA/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Stand-up, writing and roast comedy===\nRoss began performing stand-up in 1994 at [[open mic]] nights at The Boston Comedy Club, a now defunct comedy venue in New York City.<ref name=CAPEARGUS>{{cite news |last=Thangevelo |first=Debashine |date=November 19, 2015 |title=Feel the burn of Ross\u2019s roast . . . |url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/cape-argus/20151119/textview |work=[[Cape Argus]] |location=Cape Town, South Africa |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> By 1995 he was also performing at such comedy clubs as the [[Comedy Cellar]] and [[Stand Up NY]].<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 28, 1995 |title=Comedy |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=meMCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA151 |magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> That same year he was invited by the [[New York Friars Club]] to participate in a roast of actor [[Steven Seagal]].<ref name=SANLUIS/><ref name=CHICAGOTRIB/>\n\nRoss became a regular at the Friars Club roasts and was given the title of \"Roastmaster General\".<ref name=MONTREALGAZ>{{cite news |last=Brownstein |first=Bill |date=July 9, 2011 |title=Just for Laughs 2011: Roastmaster Jeffrey Ross has a serious side |url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/just+laughs+2011+roastmaster+jeffrey+ross+serious+side/5073993/story.html |work=[[Montreal Gazette]] |location=Montreal, Quebec, Canada |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bliss |first=Jessica |date=March 13, 2012 |title=Roastmaster General takes aim at Nashville |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/218621839/ |work=[[The Tennessean]] |location=Nashville, Tennessee, United States |page=3A |access-date=May 1, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription |quote=The roastmaster designation is a title bestowed upon him by the New York Friar's Club, a private fraternity in New York City made up most of famous comedians.}}</ref> The Friars Club's first televised event was the roast of [[Drew Carey]] that was broadcast on [[Comedy Central]] in 1998.<ref name=PLAYBOY/><ref name=ROLLING2>{{cite magazine |last=Love |first=Matthew |date=March 13, 2015 |title=Every Comedy Central Roast, From Worst to Best |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-lists/every-comedy-central-roast-from-worst-to-best-178245/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Ross credits a particular joke that he made at the expense of attendees [[Bea Arthur]] and [[Sandra Bernhardt]] at the 1999 roast of [[Jerry Stiller]] for taking his roasting career to the next level.<ref>{{cite news |last=Holtzclaw |first=Mike |date=June 18, 2015 |title=The host with the 'roasts': Comedian Jeff Ross brings merciless style of stand-up to The Norva |url=https://www.dailypress.com/entertainment/dp-fea-jeff-ross-0619-20150618-story.html |work=[[Daily Press (Virginia)]] |location=Newport News, Virginia, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=It was in that role, at a 1999 roast of Jerry Stiller, that Ross got off an unspeakably vulgar zinger that simultaneously nailed both Sandra Bernhard and Bea Arthur (though Ross notes that it was Arthur's wordless \"stink-eye\" reaction that elevated the joke to comedic genius). To this day, he says, that is the joke that truly took his career to a higher level, the one that people still repeat to him.}}</ref> That same year [[Jimmy Kimmel]] hired Ross as a writer on ''[[The Man Show]]'' and Ross also wrote some of the punchlines for [[Billy Crystal]]'s monologue at the [[Academy Awards|Oscars]] in 2000.<ref name=PLAYBOY/>\n\nIn 2003 Comedy Central began producing their own celebrity roasts.<ref name=ROLLING2/> Ross has been a roaster at all Comedy Central roasts since the 2005 roast of [[Pamela Anderson]].<ref name=NPR/><ref name=SANLUIS/> During his ''Comedy Central Roast'' appearances Ross became known for dressing-up in edgy and sometimes controversial costumes: He roasted [[Charlie Sheen]] dressed as [[Muammar Gaddafi]]; he roasted [[Rob Lowe]] dressed as ''[[Purple Rain (film)|Purple Rain]]''-era [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] on an episode that aired five months after the musician's death; he roasted [[Roseanne Barr]] dressed as the late football coach [[Joe Paterno]] during the height of the [[Penn State child sex abuse scandal]]; he also roasted [[James Franco]] wearing [[cornrows]] and a neck tattoo in reference to Franco's character in the 2012 film ''[[Spring Breakers]]''.<ref name=PLAYBOY/><ref>{{cite news |last=Venutolo |first=Anthony |date=August 6, 2012 |title=Did comic Jeffrey Ross go too far at Roseanne's roast? |url=https://www.nj.com/inside-jersey/2011/09/take_5_with_jeffrey_ross.html |work=NJ.com |location=Iselin, New Jersey, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRoss has participated as a roaster on the following [[Comedy Central Roast]]s: \n{{div col}}\n* [[Pamela Anderson]] (2005)\n* [[William Shatner]] (2006)\n* [[Flavor Flav]] (2007)\n* [[Bob Saget]] (2008)\n* [[Larry the Cable Guy]] (2009)\n* [[Joan Rivers]] (2009)\n* [[David Hasselhoff]] (2010)\n* [[Donald Trump]] (2011)\n* [[Charlie Sheen]] (2011)\n* [[Roseanne Barr]] (2012)\n* [[James Franco]] (2013)\n* [[Justin Bieber]] (2015)\n* [[Rob Lowe]] (2016)\n* [[Mexico\u2013United States border|The Border]] (2017)\n* [[Bruce Willis]] (2018)\n* [[Alec Baldwin]] (2019)\n{{div col end}}\nRoss has also written for, performed in and/or produced the roasts of the following celebrities:\n{{div col}}\n* [[Drew Carey]] (1998), produced by the New York Friars Club\n* [[Jerry Stiller]] (1999), produced by the New York Friars Club\n* [[Rob Reiner]] (2000), produced by the New York Friars Club\n* [[Hugh Hefner]] (2001), produced by the New York Friars Club\n* [[Carson Daly]] (2003), produced by [[MTV]]\n* [[Gene Simmons]] (2008), produced by [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]\n* [[Emmitt Smith]] (2008), produced by [[Shaquille O'Neal]] in the second installment of his TV series ''Shaq's All Star Comedy Roast''\n* [[Mike Greenberg]] and [[Mike Golic]] (aka ''[[Mike & Mike]]'') (2008), produced by [[ESPN]]\n{{div col end}}\n[[File:160505-D-DB155-011 Comedian Jeff Ross at Joint Base Andrews in May 2016.jpg |thumb |left |Ross at [[Joint Base Andrews]] in May 2016]]\nRoss has taken part in several [[USO]] tours and has performed stand-up comedy at US Military bases in [[Afghanistan]], [[Guantanamo Bay]] and [[Iraq]].<ref name=PLAYBOY/> Ross first traveled to Iraq in 2003 as part of a comedy tour hosted by [[Drew Carey]].<ref name=NYTIRAQ>{{cite news |last=Heffernan |first=Virginia |date=May 27, 2006 |title=The Iraq Tour: A Comic's Education |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/27/arts/television/27heff.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In 2005 Ross released the film ''[[Patriot Act: A Jeffrey Ross Home Movie]]'', which he both produced and directed and which documented his experiences on the Iraq tour.<ref name=NYTIRAQ/> That same year the film won the prize for Best Film at the [[Comedia (festival)|Comedia film festival]], a comedy film festival held annually in [[Montreal]] as part of the [[Just for Laughs]] comedy festival.<ref name=PASTEPATRIOT>{{cite magazine |last=Zaino III |first=Nick A. |date=September 28, 2005 |title=Comedia: Laughing Stock of Film Festivals |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2005/09/comedia-laughing-stock-of-film-festivals.html |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |location=Decatur, Georgia, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In 2006 the film was shown on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] and also screened at that year's [[South by Southwest Film Festival]].<ref name=NYTIRAQ/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sxsw.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/2006_archive_-_final.pdf |title=SXSW Film Festival 2006 Line Up |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=sxsw.com |publisher=[[South by Southwest]] |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In 2017 the USO made Ross the Ambassador of Veterans Outreach for the Artists & Athletes Alliance.<ref name=LAWEEKLY>{{cite news |last=Seabaugh |first=Julie |date=November 14, 2017 |title=Is Jeff Ross the Most Important Political Comic in Trump's America? |url=https://www.laweekly.com/arts/jeff-ross-might-be-the-most-important-political-comic-in-trumps-america-8831009 |work=[[LA Weekly]] |location=Los Angeles, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRoss published his first book, ''I Only Roast the Ones I Love: Busting Balls Without Burning Bridges'', in 2009.<ref name=LAWEEKLY/><ref name=SIMON>{{cite book |last=Ross |first=Jeffrey |date=2009 |title=I Only Roast the Ones I Love: Busting Balls Without Burning Bridges |url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/I-Only-Roast-the-Ones-I-Love/Jeffrey-Ross/9781439102794 |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=9781439102794 |author-link=Jeff Ross}}</ref> The book recounts his journey to becoming Roastmaster General and includes tips on writing roast jokes and how to put on a roast.<ref name=LAWEEKLY/><ref name=SIMON/>\n\nRoss was the creator and host of the comedy [[panel show]] ''[[The Burn with Jeff Ross]]'', which aired on Comedy Central for two seasons from 2012 to 2013.<ref name=MORNINGCALL>{{cite news |last=Moser |first=John J. |date=March 23, 2018 |title=INTERVIEW: Comedian Jeff Ross, at Sands today with Dave Attell, tells how venue gave birth to the tour, talks about roasting career and new podcast |url=https://www.mcall.com/entertainment/lehigh-valley-music/mc-ent-jeff-ross-interview-dave-attell-sands-bethlehem-event-center-20180323-story.html |work=[[The Morning Call]] |location=Allentown, Pennsylvania, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Ross starred in the Comedy Central special ''Jeff Ross Roasts Criminals: Live from Brazos County Jail'', where he performed stand-up comedy for male and female convicts in [[Brazos County, Texas]].<ref name=ROLLING>{{cite magazine |last=Blistein |first=Jon |date=March 31, 2016 |title=Jeff Ross \u2018Roast Battle,\u2019 \u2018Police Roast\u2019 Headed to Comedy Central |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/jeff-ross-roast-battle-police-roast-headed-to-comedy-central-63162/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=INTERROBANG>{{cite web |url=https://theinterrobang.com/comedy-roast-competition-coming-television/ |title=Finally, the Comedy Roast Competition Battle is Coming to Television |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 31, 2016 |website=The Interrobang |publisher=Orange Pop Media |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> The following year he released ''Jeff Ross Roasts Cops'' where he performed for members of the [[Boston Police Department]].<ref name=NPR/><ref name=LAWEEKLY/>\n\nRoss and comedian Brian Moses launched ''[[Jeff Ross Presents Roast Battle]]'' on Comedy Central in 2016.<ref name=ROLLING/> The show consists of comedians competing in one-on-one roast battles where the winners are decided by Ross and a panel of guest judges.<ref name=ROLLING/><ref name=INTERROBANG/> Ross also appeared as a battler in final episode of the show's third season in a battle with [[NBA]] player [[Blake Griffin]].<ref name=CCPRESS2>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 31, 2018 |title=Comedy Central Announces Judges, Battler for Season 3 of Jeff Ross Presents Roast Battle |url=https://press.cc.com/press-release/2018/07/23/press-jeff-ross-presents-roast-battle-season-3-premieres-tuesday-july-31-at-10-p-m |location=New York |publisher=Comedy Central |access-date=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Ross and fellow comedian [[Dave Attell]] embarked on their ''Bumping Mics'' comedy tour.<ref name=INTERROBANG3>{{cite web |url=https://theinterrobang.com/dave-attell-jeffrey-ross-two-giants-bumping-mics-tour/ |title=Dave Attell and Jeffrey Ross: Two Giants, Bumping Mics on Tour |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 1, 2018 |website=The Interrobang |publisher=Orange Pop Media |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Footage of their tour was also released in a three-part special on [[Netflix]].<ref name=UPI>{{cite news |last=Hooper |first=Ben |date=December 7, 2018 |title=Attell and Ross: 'Real hero' of 'Bumping Mics' is 'the punchline' |url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2018/12/07/Attell-and-Ross-Real-hero-of-Bumping-Mics-is-the-punchline/8331544123726/ |work=[[United Press International]] |location=Boca Raton, Florida, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> The ''Bumping Mics'' comedy special was filmed during three of their performances at the [[Comedy Cellar]] in New York City.<ref name=UPI/> Their shows consisted of [[observational humor|observational]] and [[political humor]] interspersed with Ross and Attell roasting one another as well as members of the audience.<ref name=DAILYFREEPRESS>{{cite news |last=Wiener |first=Sophie |date=November 30, 2018 |title=REVIEW: \u2018Bumping Mics with Jeff Ross and Dave Attell\u2019 is crude and mean, yet heartwarming |url=https://dailyfreepress.com/blog/2018/11/30/review-bumping-mics-with-jeff-ross-and-dave-attell-is-crude-and-mean-yet-heartwarming/ |work=[[The Daily Free Press]] |location=Boston, Massachusetts, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=INTERROBANG2>{{cite web |url=https://theinterrobang.com/bumping-mics-dave-attell-jeff-ross-jfl/ |title=Bumping Mics With Dave Attell and Jeff Ross at JFL |last=Dahms |first=Sara |date=July 27, 2017 |website=The Interrobang |publisher=Orange Pop Media |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> The comedians also invited audience members onto the stage, some of whom included [[Bob Saget]], [[Gilbert Gottfried]], [[Michael Che]], [[Amy Schumer]], [[Nikki Glaser]] and [[Paul Rudd]].<ref name=UPI/>\n\nStarting in 2019, [[Netflix]] began airing the series ''[[Historical Roasts]]'', where Ross hosts fictionalized versions of comedy roasts for figures like [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Anne Frank]].\n\n===Acting and voice work===\nOne of Ross's first acting roles was a small part in the 1996 comedy film ''[[Celtic Pride]]''.<ref name=HUFFPO>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/21/jeffrey-ross-at-occupy-la_n_1026084.html |title=Jeffrey Ross At Occupy LA: Part Stand Up, Part Soap Box |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 21, 2011 |website=[[The Huffington Post]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uproxx.com/tv/jeff-ross-dressed-as-joe-paterno/ |title=Jeff Ross Went To Roseanne\u2019s Comedy Central Roast Dressed As Joe Paterno |last=Kurp |first=Josh |date=August 5, 2012 |website=[[Uproxx]] |publisher= |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Some of his other film roles include a security guard the film ''[[Stuck on You (2003 film)|Stuck on You]]'' (2003) and a wedding band leader in the film ''[[Along Came Polly]]'' (2004).<ref name=VARIETY2/><ref name=LAIST>{{cite news |last=H |first=Tim |date=April 22, 2010 |title=Seven Questions: Jeffrey Ross, Comedian/Author of I Only Roast the Ones I Love |url=https://laist.com/2010/04/22/seven_questions_jeffrey_ross_comedi.php |work=[[LAist]] |location=Los Angeles, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505192835/https://laist.com/2010/04/22/seven_questions_jeffrey_ross_comedi.php |archive-date=May 5, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ross's television acting work includes roles on [[HBO]]'s ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'' and ''[[Crashing (U.S. TV series)|Crashing]]'', and [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]''.<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/><ref>{{cite news |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=March 8, 2019 |title='Crashing' canceled after three seasons at HBO |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/tv/ct-ent-crashing-canceled-20190308-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, Illinois, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> He also played a dramatic role on [[CBS]]'s ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]''.<ref name=VARIETY2/><ref name=MONTREALGAZ/>\n\nRoss was co-creator of the [[satire|satirical]] animated program ''[[Where My Dogs At?]]'' that was broadcast on [[MTV2]] in 2006. The series centers around characters Buddy, a [[beagle]] voiced by Ross, and Woof, a [[bulldog]] voiced by [[Tracy Morgan]].<ref name=IGN>{{cite web |url=https://ca.ign.com/articles/2006/06/06/jeffrey-ross-on-where-my-dogs-at |title=Jeffrey Ross on Where My Dogs At? |last=Zoromski |first=Brian |date=June 6, 2006 |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |location=San Francisco, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019 |quote=}}</ref> Ross has also voiced a characters on two episodes of the animated series ''[[Future-Worm!]]'' as well as on an episode of the [[live-action animated film|live-action/animated]] series ''[[Happy! (TV series)|Happy!]]''<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Flores |first=Terry |date=July 28, 2016 |title=Get to Know Ryan Quincy, Creator of Disney XD\u2019s New Series \u2018Future-Worm\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/comedy-central-jeff-ross-roast-battle-1201909718/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |location=Los Angeles, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/realjeffreyross/status/1121181826624581633 |title=@realjeffreyross |date=April 24, 2019 |website=Twitter |access-date=May 1, 2019 |quote=I play Pile Of Twigs and @pattonoswalt plays a unicorn named Happy on tonight\u2019s episode of \u201cHappy\u201d. Watch and enjoy 10pm on @SYFY if you\u2019re a dark fucked up person. #SeeHappy @happysyfy}}</ref> An animated version of Jeff Ross (voiced by Ross himself) appears in an episode of ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]'' that aired in 2012.<ref name=CITYPAGES>{{cite news |last=Strait |first=Patrick |date=January 31, 2012 |title=Jeff Ross talks Batman, losing his virginity, roasting Minnesota |url=http://www.citypages.com/arts/jeff-ross-talks-batman-losing-his-virginity-roasting-minnesota-6587278 |work=[[City Pages]] |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019 }}</ref> During the episode his character attends a roast of [[Batman (comics)|Batman]].<ref name=CITYPAGES/>\n\n===Other appearances as himself===\nRoss appeared in the 2005 documentary ''[[The Aristocrats (film)|The Aristocrats]]'' about the famous [[The Aristocrats |dirty joke of the same name]].<ref name=LAIST/>\n\nHe was the guest on the debut episode of the ''[[WTF with Marc Maron]]'' podcast in 2009 and also appeared on the podcast's 800<sup>th</sup> episode in 2017.<ref name=LAWEEKLY/>\n\nRoss appeared in the third tournament of [[Celebrity Poker]] in 2004, but lost in his first match.<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/> He was also a competitor on the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 7)|seventh season]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' that aired in 2008.<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/> During rehearsal for their first dance, his dancing partner [[Edyta \u015aliwi\u0144ska]] accidentally poked Ross in the eye, causing a scratched [[cornea]].<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/>  Against medical advice, Ross continued the competition, but the couple were the first to be eliminated.<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/>\n\nIn 2011 Ross visited the protesters of the [[Occupy movement]] in Los Angeles to support their cause.<ref name=HUFFPO/> He took to the microphone at a stage set-up at [[Los Angeles City Hall]].<ref name=HUFFPO/> His talk included roasting [[Wall Street]] and the [[Big_Four_(banking)#United_States|big banks]].<ref name=HUFFPO/>\n\nIn 2019, he appeared on an episode of \u2018\u2019[[Crank Yankers]]\u2019\u2019 as himself.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Celtic Pride]]''\n| Car Theft Victim\n| \n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Taxman (film)|Taxman]]''\n| Tax Collector\n| \n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Isn't She Great]]''\n| Shecky\n| \n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle (film)|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle]]''\n| District Attorney\n| \n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[National Security (2003 film)|National Security]]''\n| Security Guard\n| \n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Stuck on You (film)|Stuck on You]]''\n| Beaze Security Guard\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Along Came Polly]]''\n| Wedding Band Leader\n| \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[American Dreamz]]''\n| Oscar\n| \n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Farce of the Penguins]]''\n| Funny-Looking Bastard (voice)\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[One, Two, Many]]''\n| Ernie\n| Direct-to-video\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[A Novel Romance]]''\n| Douglas Silver\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Wedding Ringer]]''\n| Hal Lane\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Flock of Dudes]]''\n| Masturbator\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Comedian (2016 film)|The Comedian]]''\n| \n| Writer\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Emoji Movie]]''\n| Internet Troll (voice)\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Dr. Katz, Professional Therapist]]''\n| Jeffrey (voice)\n| Episode: \"Blind Date\"\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Cosby]]''\n| Carl\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Shasta McNasty]]''\n| Bank Manager\n| Episode: \"True Size\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Greg the Bunny]]''\n| Security Guard\n| Episode: \"Welcome to Sweetknuckle Junction\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]''\n| Shiva Comic\n| Episode: \"Back to the Garden\"\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]''\n| Dougie Max\n| Episode: \"Last Laugh\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]''\n| Billy\n| Episode: \"Dead in the Nethers\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Where My Dogs At?]]''\n| Buddy (voice)\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Sarah Silverman Program]]''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"Ah, Men\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Childrens Hospital]]''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"Joke Overload\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Big Time Rush]]''\n| Insult Comic\n| Episode: \"Big Time Guru\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| Episode: \"Crisis: 22,300 Miles Above Earth!\"\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| ''[[The Burn with Jeff Ross]]''\n| Himself\n| 12 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Drunk History]]''\n| [[Francis Scott Key]]\n| Episode: \"Baltimore\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| Episode: \"[[Clown in the Dumps]]\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|Comedy Bang! Bang!]]''\n| Himself \n| Episode: \"Amber Tamblyn Wears a Leather Jacket & Black Booties\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Grandfathered (TV series)|Grandfathered]]''\n| Marv\n| Episode: \"Some Guy I'm Seeing\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Dr. Ken]]''\n| Doug\n| Episode: \"Ken Tries Standup\"\n|-\n| 2016\u20132018\n| ''[[Jeff Ross Presents Roast Battle]]''\n| Himself\n| 19 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Future-Worm!]]''\n| Mr. Bleaker (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018\n| ''[[Crashing (American TV series)|Crashing]]''\n| Himself\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n| ''[[Rapunzel's Tangled Adventure]]''\n| Hook Foot\n| 24 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[American Dad!]]''\n| Chief Danny (voice)\n| Episode: \"Camp Campawanda\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Penn Zero: Part-Time Hero]]''\n| Sonny (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Teachers (2016 TV series)|Teachers]]''\n| Fire Marshal Brownstein\n| Episode: \"Toxic Workplace\"\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Sneaky Pete]]''\n| D.C. Doug\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Happy! (TV series)|Happy!]]''\n| Twigs (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Historical Roasts]]''\n| Himself\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Crank Yankers]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| Episode: \"Jimmy Kimmel, Kathy Griffin & Jeff Ross\"\n|-\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n* ''No Offense'' (2008, [[Shout! Factory]]) - CD/DVD/Download\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jeff Ross}}\n*{{official website}}\n*{{IMDb name|743506|Jeff Ross}}\n* [https://archive.is/20100724224142/http://www.comedyhalloffame.com/archives/jeffrey-ross/ Jeff Ross] at Comedy Hall of Fame Archives\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ross, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:American comedy writers]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Communications alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American comedians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Springfield Township, Union County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American stand-up comedian, insult comic, actor, and director}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name = Jeff Ross\n| image = Jeff Ross, Joint Base Andrews, May 2016 (cropped).jpg\n| caption =  Ross in May 2016\n| birth_name = Jeffrey Ross Lifschultz\n| pseudonym = Roastmaster General\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1965|9|13}}\n| birth_place = <!-- PLEASE NOTE: Any addition to this field without a properly cited reference will be reverted. If you need help, please post an edit request to the article's talk page -->\n| medium = [[Stand-up]], [[television]], [[film]], [[books]]\n| active = 1994\u2013present\n| genre = [[Insult comedy]], [[observational comedy]], [[black comedy]], [[cringe comedy]], [[satire]]\n| subject = [[Jewish culture]], [[popular culture]], [[self-deprecation]], [[sex]], [[current events]], [[religion]]\n| notable_work = [[Comedy Central Roasts]]<br/>''[[Patriot Act: A Jeffrey Ross Home Movie]]''<br/>''[[The Burn with Jeff Ross]]''\n}}\n'''Jeffrey Ross Lifschultz''' (born September 13, 1965),<ref name=HAARETZ>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 13, 2018 |title=Jewish Insider's Daily Kickoff: September 13, 2018 - Birthdays |url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/jewish-insider-s-daily-kickoff-september-13-2018-1.6470421 |work=[[Haaretz]] |location=Tel Aviv, Israel |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=Comedian who earned the title \"Roastmaster General\" for his [[insult comedy]] and Comedy Central celebrity roasts, Jeff Ross (born Jeffrey Ross Lifschultz) turns 53...}}</ref> known professionally as '''Jeff Ross''', is an American stand-up comedian, writer, director and actor. He is also known as the \"'''Roastmaster General'''\" for his [[insult comedy]] and his multiple appearances at celebrity [[Roast (comedy)|roasts]] held by the [[New York Friars Club]] and on the ''[[Comedy Central Roast]]'' television series.<ref name=NPR>{{Cite episode |title=Having Thick Skin Is A 'Survival Technique,' Says Comic Jeff Ross |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/13/493688206/having-thick-skin-is-a-survival-technique-says-comic-jeff-ross |access-date=May 1, 2019 |series=Fresh Air |series-link=Fresh Air |first=Gross |last=Terry |network=NPR |date=September 13, 2016 |time=0:30 |quote=...but he's best known for the Comedy Central celebrity roasts; he's one of the producers and has been a roaster on each one since 2005.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Zinoman |first=Jason |date=July 29, 2016 |title=Insult Comedy as Blood Sport: The Rise of the Roast Battle |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/30/arts/television/insult-comedy-as-blood-sport-the-rise-of-the-roast-battle.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=When Mr. Ross, who had become known as the Roastmaster General because of his performances on Comedy Central\u2019s celebrity events...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pilot |first=Jessica |date=November 7, 2014 |title=The Roast Battle: \u2018Like Fight Club for Comedians,\u2019 Says Jeffrey Ross |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2014/11/07/the-roast-battle-like-fight-club-for-comedians-says-jeffrey-ross/ |work=[[The Village Voice]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=Today, Jeff Ross is practically a household name. He has been the Roastmaster at the venerable Friars Club, and is part of every Comedy Central Roast...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Brownstein |first=Bill |date=July 9, 2011 |title=Just for Laughs 2011: Roastmaster Jeffrey Ross has a serious side |url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/just+laughs+2011+roastmaster+jeffrey+ross+serious+side/5073993/story.html |work=[[Montreal Gazette]] |location=Montreal, Quebec, Canada |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=Ross is the current New York Friars\u2019 Club Roastmaster General and a regular on the Comedy Central Roasts.}}</ref> In 2009 the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' called Ross \"the new millennium [[Don Rickles]].\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Steve |date=October 13, 2009 |title=Mr. Cruel |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2009-10-13-0910130087-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, Illinois, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=He got to this place, as the new millennium Don Rickles, partly thanks to an insult-loving uncle, partly as a result of working in his dad's New Jersey catering business, where a multicultural work crew loved to bust on the boss' son.}}</ref> His directorial debut, the 2006 documentary ''[[Patriot Act: A Jeffrey Ross Home Movie]]'', won the prize for Best Film at the [[Comedia (festival)|Comedia film festival]] held at the [[Just for Laughs]] comedy festival in [[Montreal]].<ref name=VARIETY2>{{cite magazine |last=Adalian |first=Josef |date=October 20, 2004 |title=Ross roasts lead to toast from Fox |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/comedy-central-jeff-ross-roast-battle-1201909718/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |location=Los Angeles, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=PASTEPATRIOT>{{cite magazine |last=Zaino III |first=Nick A. |date=September 28, 2005 |title=Comedia: Laughing Stock of Film Festivals |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2005/09/comedia-laughing-stock-of-film-festivals.html |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |location=Decatur, Georgia, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRoss was raised in [[Newark, New Jersey]], until he was in second grade; then his family moved to [[Union, New Jersey]]{{dn|date=October 2019}}, and later to [[Springfield Township, Union County, New Jersey|Springfield, New Jersey]], where he attended [[Jonathan Dayton High School]].<ref name=NJ>{{cite news |last=Considine |first=Bob |date=September 29, 2011 |title=Take 5 with Jeffrey Ross |url=https://www.nj.com/inside-jersey/2011/09/take_5_with_jeffrey_ross.html|archivedate=May 2, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190502051415/https://www.nj.com/inside-jersey/2011/09/take_5_with_jeffrey_ross.html|url-status=live|work=[[The Star-Ledger]] |location=Newark, New Jersey, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=I grew up in Newark, Union and Springfield. ... So we lived in Newark until I was in second grade, then we jumped to Union and then to Springfield, where I kind of stayed for a while. I lost my Mom when I was 14 and my Dad when I was 19...}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url= https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/I-Only-Roast-the-Ones-I-Love/Jeffrey-Ross/9781439102794 |title=I Only Roast the Ones I Love: Busting Balls Without Burning Bridges|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|page=64 |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=It wasn't until I reached Jonathan Dayton Regional High School in Springfield that I discovered the great power of the put-down.}}</ref> He is of [[Jewish]] heritage and has a younger sister named Robyn.<ref name=HAARETZ/><ref name=ISRAEL>{{cite news |last=Wootliff |first=Raoul |date=January 10, 2018 |title=Chris Rock bares soul in roaringly honest Israel debut |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/chris-rock-bares-soul-in-roaringly-honest-israel-debut/ |work= |location= |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=Veteran roaster Jeff Ross..repeatedly told the audience of his Jewish roots, noting, \u201cI love my people and you are my people...\u201d }}</ref><ref name=PLAYBOY>{{cite magazine |last=Buckland |first=Jason |date=January 27, 2017 |title=Roastmaster General Jeffrey Ross Stands Up for More than Comedy |url=http://www.playboy.com/articles/jeff-ross-profile |url-status=live |magazine=[[Playboy]] |location=Chicago, Illinois, United States |publisher=Playboy Enterprises |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313135521/http://www.playboy.com/articles/jeff-ross-profile |archive-date=March 13, 2017 |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> His mother Marsha died from [[leukemia]] when he was 14 years old.<ref name=NJ/><ref name=PLAYBOY/><ref name=NPRPARENTS>{{Cite episode |title=Having Thick Skin Is A 'Survival Technique,' Says Comic Jeff Ross | url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/13/493688206/having-thick-skin-is-a-survival-technique-says-comic-jeff-ross |access-date=April 21, 2019 |series=Fresh Air |series-link=Fresh Air |first=Gross |last=Terry |network=NPR |date=September 13, 2016 |time=29:05 |quote=Terry Gross: \"So you mention your parents. Your mother died when you were 14. Did she have cancer?\" Jeff Ross: \"She had leukemia.\" TG: \"Then your father died when you were 19; that was sudden and unexpected.\" JR: \"Yeah, doin' stupid stuff. Drugs.\" TG: \"Oh really?\" JR: \"He was a single guy starting to make money in the 80s. I was away at college, my sister was a senior in highschool.\"}}</ref> His father died of drug-related causes when Ross was 19 years old\u2014Ross was attending college at the time and his sister was a [[Senior (education)|senior]] in high school.<ref name=NJ/><ref name=NPRPARENTS/> His father owned and ran Clinton Manor Catering, a [[catering]] business that was started by Ross's great-grandmother.<ref name=NPRCLINTON>{{Cite episode |title=Having Thick Skin Is A 'Survival Technique,' Says Comic Jeff Ross |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/13/493688206/having-thick-skin-is-a-survival-technique-says-comic-jeff-ross |access-date=April 21, 2019 |series=Fresh Air |series-link=Fresh Air |first=Gross |last=Terry |network=NPR |date=September 13, 2016 |time=27:23 |quote=My great grandmother Rose, she started it a long time ago in the 50s...It was in Newark, New Jersey, and then later in Union, New Jersey. It was called Clinton Manor Catering. Judy Bloom wrote about it in her book \"Wifey\".}}</ref>  The business was located in [[Newark, New Jersey]], and later moved to [[Union, New Jersey]].{{dn|date=October 2019}}<ref name=NPRCLINTON/>\n\nRoss attended [[Boston University]] as a [[broadcasting]] and [[film]] [[Major (academic)|major]] with a [[Minor (academic)|minor]] in [[political science]].<ref name=SANLUIS>{{cite news |last=Pemberton |first=Patrick S. |date=October 2, 2014 |title=Roastmaster General: Comedian Jeff Ross on the art of the roast |url=https://www.sanluisobispo.com/entertainment/arts-culture/article39498495.html |work=[[The Tribune (San Luis Obispo)|The Tribune]] |location=San Luis Obispo County, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=After losing both parents while in his teens, the New Jersey native studied communications at Boston University...}}</ref> <ref name=CAPECOD>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Jim |date=July 31, 2017 |title=Jeff Ross: Roastmaster General |url=https://www.capecodtimes.com/entertainmentlife/20170731/jeff-ross-roastmaster-general |work=[[Cape Cod Times]] |location=Hyannis, Massachusetts, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> He graduated from the [[Boston University College of Communication]] in 1987.<ref name=CAPECOD/> Ross also worked as the music director at the university's student-run radio station [[WTBU (Boston University)|WTBU]] in addition to working for the university's [[public radio]] station [[WBUR]] where he worked as an [[audio engineer]].<ref name=CAPECOD/>\n\nRoss credits his tough upbringing in New Jersey for helping him develop his talent for insult comedy, which he says he developed as a defense mechanism.<ref name=CHICAGOTRIB>{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Steve |date=October 13, 2009 |title=Mr. Cruel |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2009-10-13-0910130087-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, Illinois, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=ATLANTA>{{cite news |last=Ho |first=Rodney |date=July 18, 2014 |title='Roastmaster General' born to insult |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/423299230/ |work=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |location=Dunwoody, Georgia, United States |page=D4 |access-date=May 1, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com ||url-access=subscription|quote=Ross said his ability to insult people goes back to childhood in New Jersey. 'Everyone in my family was good at it. I had to quickly learn not just to take a joke but to give it back. My uncle Murray was the first to bust my chops. We called him mean Murray. He'd make fun of my braces, my buck teeth. I worked at my parent's catering hall and was the boss' son.  He would give me a lot of crap.'}}</ref> Ross stated in an interview with ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'': \"Everyone in my family was good at [roasting]. I had to quickly learn not just to take a joke but to give it back. My uncle Murray was the first to bust my chops. We called him mean Murray.\"<ref name=ATLANTA/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Stand-up, writing and roast comedy===\nRoss began performing stand-up in 1994 at [[open mic]] nights at The Boston Comedy Club, a now defunct comedy venue in New York City.<ref name=CAPEARGUS>{{cite news |last=Thangevelo |first=Debashine |date=November 19, 2015 |title=Feel the burn of Ross\u2019s roast . . . |url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/cape-argus/20151119/textview |work=[[Cape Argus]] |location=Cape Town, South Africa |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> By 1995 he was also performing at such comedy clubs as the [[Comedy Cellar]] and [[Stand Up NY]].<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=August 28, 1995 |title=Comedy |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=meMCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA151 |magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> That same year he was invited by the [[New York Friars Club]] to participate in a roast of actor [[Steven Seagal]].<ref name=SANLUIS/><ref name=CHICAGOTRIB/>\n\nRoss became a regular at the Friars Club roasts and was given the title of \"Roastmaster General\".<ref name=MONTREALGAZ>{{cite news |last=Brownstein |first=Bill |date=July 9, 2011 |title=Just for Laughs 2011: Roastmaster Jeffrey Ross has a serious side |url=http://www.montrealgazette.com/entertainment/just+laughs+2011+roastmaster+jeffrey+ross+serious+side/5073993/story.html |work=[[Montreal Gazette]] |location=Montreal, Quebec, Canada |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bliss |first=Jessica |date=March 13, 2012 |title=Roastmaster General takes aim at Nashville |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/218621839/ |work=[[The Tennessean]] |location=Nashville, Tennessee, United States |page=3A |access-date=May 1, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription |quote=The roastmaster designation is a title bestowed upon him by the New York Friar's Club, a private fraternity in New York City made up most of famous comedians.}}</ref> The Friars Club's first televised event was the roast of [[Drew Carey]] that was broadcast on [[Comedy Central]] in 1998.<ref name=PLAYBOY/><ref name=ROLLING2>{{cite magazine |last=Love |first=Matthew |date=March 13, 2015 |title=Every Comedy Central Roast, From Worst to Best |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-lists/every-comedy-central-roast-from-worst-to-best-178245/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Ross credits a particular joke that he made at the expense of attendees [[Bea Arthur]] and [[Sandra Bernhardt]] at the 1999 roast of [[Jerry Stiller]] for taking his roasting career to the next level.<ref>{{cite news |last=Holtzclaw |first=Mike |date=June 18, 2015 |title=The host with the 'roasts': Comedian Jeff Ross brings merciless style of stand-up to The Norva |url=https://www.dailypress.com/entertainment/dp-fea-jeff-ross-0619-20150618-story.html |work=[[Daily Press (Virginia)]] |location=Newport News, Virginia, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019|quote=It was in that role, at a 1999 roast of Jerry Stiller, that Ross got off an unspeakably vulgar zinger that simultaneously nailed both Sandra Bernhard and Bea Arthur (though Ross notes that it was Arthur's wordless \"stink-eye\" reaction that elevated the joke to comedic genius). To this day, he says, that is the joke that truly took his career to a higher level, the one that people still repeat to him.}}</ref> That same year [[Jimmy Kimmel]] hired Ross as a writer on ''[[The Man Show]]'' and Ross also wrote some of the punchlines for [[Billy Crystal]]'s monologue at the [[Academy Awards|Oscars]] in 2000.<ref name=PLAYBOY/>\n\nIn 2003 Comedy Central began producing their own celebrity roasts.<ref name=ROLLING2/> Ross has been a roaster at all Comedy Central roasts since the 2005 roast of [[Pamela Anderson]].<ref name=NPR/><ref name=SANLUIS/> During his ''Comedy Central Roast'' appearances Ross became known for dressing-up in edgy and sometimes controversial costumes: He roasted [[Charlie Sheen]] dressed as [[Muammar Gaddafi]]; he roasted [[Rob Lowe]] dressed as ''[[Purple Rain (film)|Purple Rain]]''-era [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] on an episode that aired five months after the musician's death; he roasted [[Roseanne Barr]] dressed as the late football coach [[Joe Paterno]] during the height of the [[Penn State child sex abuse scandal]]; he also roasted [[James Franco]] wearing [[cornrows]] and a neck tattoo in reference to Franco's character in the 2012 film ''[[Spring Breakers]]''.<ref name=PLAYBOY/><ref>{{cite news |last=Venutolo |first=Anthony |date=August 6, 2012 |title=Did comic Jeffrey Ross go too far at Roseanne's roast? |url=https://www.nj.com/inside-jersey/2011/09/take_5_with_jeffrey_ross.html |work=NJ.com |location=Iselin, New Jersey, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRoss has participated as a roaster on the following [[Comedy Central Roast]]s: \n{{div col}}\n* [[Pamela Anderson]] (2005)\n* [[William Shatner]] (2006)\n* [[Flavor Flav]] (2007)\n* [[Bob Saget]] (2008)\n* [[Larry the Cable Guy]] (2009)\n* [[Joan Rivers]] (2009)\n* [[David Hasselhoff]] (2010)\n* [[Donald Trump]] (2011)\n* [[Charlie Sheen]] (2011)\n* [[Roseanne Barr]] (2012)\n* [[James Franco]] (2013)\n* [[Justin Bieber]] (2015)\n* [[Rob Lowe]] (2016)\n* [[Mexico\u2013United States border|The Border]] (2017)\n* [[Bruce Willis]] (2018)\n* [[Alec Baldwin]] (2019)\n{{div col end}}\nRoss has also written for, performed in and/or produced the roasts of the following celebrities:\n{{div col}}\n* [[Drew Carey]] (1998), produced by the New York Friars Club\n* [[Jerry Stiller]] (1999), produced by the New York Friars Club\n* [[Rob Reiner]] (2000), produced by the New York Friars Club\n* [[Hugh Hefner]] (2001), produced by the New York Friars Club\n* [[Carson Daly]] (2003), produced by [[MTV]]\n* [[Gene Simmons]] (2008), produced by [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]\n* [[Emmitt Smith]] (2008), produced by [[Shaquille O'Neal]] in the second installment of his TV series ''Shaq's All Star Comedy Roast''\n* [[Mike Greenberg]] and [[Mike Golic]] (aka ''[[Mike & Mike]]'') (2008), produced by [[ESPN]]\n{{div col end}}\n[[File:160505-D-DB155-011 Comedian Jeff Ross at Joint Base Andrews in May 2016.jpg |thumb |left |Ross at [[Joint Base Andrews]] in May 2016]]\nRoss has taken part in several [[USO]] tours and has performed stand-up comedy at US Military bases in [[Afghanistan]], [[Guantanamo Bay]] and [[Iraq]].<ref name=PLAYBOY/> Ross first traveled to Iraq in 2003 as part of a comedy tour hosted by [[Drew Carey]].<ref name=NYTIRAQ>{{cite news |last=Heffernan |first=Virginia |date=May 27, 2006 |title=The Iraq Tour: A Comic's Education |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/27/arts/television/27heff.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In 2005 Ross released the film ''[[Patriot Act: A Jeffrey Ross Home Movie]]'', which he both produced and directed and which documented his experiences on the Iraq tour.<ref name=NYTIRAQ/> That same year the film won the prize for Best Film at the [[Comedia (festival)|Comedia film festival]], a comedy film festival held annually in [[Montreal]] as part of the [[Just for Laughs]] comedy festival.<ref name=PASTEPATRIOT>{{cite magazine |last=Zaino III |first=Nick A. |date=September 28, 2005 |title=Comedia: Laughing Stock of Film Festivals |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2005/09/comedia-laughing-stock-of-film-festivals.html |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |location=Decatur, Georgia, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In 2006 the film was shown on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] and also screened at that year's [[South by Southwest Film Festival]].<ref name=NYTIRAQ/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sxsw.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/2006_archive_-_final.pdf |title=SXSW Film Festival 2006 Line Up |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=sxsw.com |publisher=[[South by Southwest]] |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In 2017 the USO made Ross the Ambassador of Veterans Outreach for the Artists & Athletes Alliance.<ref name=LAWEEKLY>{{cite news |last=Seabaugh |first=Julie |date=November 14, 2017 |title=Is Jeff Ross the Most Important Political Comic in Trump's America? |url=https://www.laweekly.com/arts/jeff-ross-might-be-the-most-important-political-comic-in-trumps-america-8831009 |work=[[LA Weekly]] |location=Los Angeles, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRoss published his first book, ''I Only Roast the Ones I Love: Busting Balls Without Burning Bridges'', in 2009.<ref name=LAWEEKLY/><ref name=SIMON>{{cite book |last=Ross |first=Jeffrey |date=2009 |title=I Only Roast the Ones I Love: Busting Balls Without Burning Bridges |url=https://www.simonandschuster.com/books/I-Only-Roast-the-Ones-I-Love/Jeffrey-Ross/9781439102794 |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=9781439102794 |author-link=Jeff Ross}}</ref> The book recounts his journey to becoming Roastmaster General and includes tips on writing roast jokes and how to put on a roast.<ref name=LAWEEKLY/><ref name=SIMON/>\n\nRoss was the creator and host of the comedy [[panel show]] ''[[The Burn with Jeff Ross]]'', which aired on Comedy Central for two seasons from 2012 to 2013.<ref name=MORNINGCALL>{{cite news |last=Moser |first=John J. |date=March 23, 2018 |title=INTERVIEW: Comedian Jeff Ross, at Sands today with Dave Attell, tells how venue gave birth to the tour, talks about roasting career and new podcast |url=https://www.mcall.com/entertainment/lehigh-valley-music/mc-ent-jeff-ross-interview-dave-attell-sands-bethlehem-event-center-20180323-story.html |work=[[The Morning Call]] |location=Allentown, Pennsylvania, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Ross starred in the Comedy Central special ''Jeff Ross Roasts Criminals: Live from Brazos County Jail'', where he performed stand-up comedy for male and female convicts in [[Brazos County, Texas]].<ref name=ROLLING>{{cite magazine |last=Blistein |first=Jon |date=March 31, 2016 |title=Jeff Ross \u2018Roast Battle,\u2019 \u2018Police Roast\u2019 Headed to Comedy Central |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-news/jeff-ross-roast-battle-police-roast-headed-to-comedy-central-63162/ |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York City, New York, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=INTERROBANG>{{cite web |url=https://theinterrobang.com/comedy-roast-competition-coming-television/ |title=Finally, the Comedy Roast Competition Battle is Coming to Television |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 31, 2016 |website=The Interrobang |publisher=Orange Pop Media |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> The following year he released ''Jeff Ross Roasts Cops'' where he performed for members of the [[Boston Police Department]].<ref name=NPR/><ref name=LAWEEKLY/>\n\nRoss and comedian Brian Moses launched ''[[Jeff Ross Presents Roast Battle]]'' on Comedy Central in 2016.<ref name=ROLLING/> The show consists of comedians competing in one-on-one roast battles where the winners are decided by Ross and a panel of guest judges.<ref name=ROLLING/><ref name=INTERROBANG/> Ross also appeared as a battler in final episode of the show's third season in a battle with [[NBA]] player [[Blake Griffin]].<ref name=CCPRESS2>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=July 31, 2018 |title=Comedy Central Announces Judges, Battler for Season 3 of Jeff Ross Presents Roast Battle |url=https://press.cc.com/press-release/2018/07/23/press-jeff-ross-presents-roast-battle-season-3-premieres-tuesday-july-31-at-10-p-m |location=New York |publisher=Comedy Central |access-date=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Ross and fellow comedian [[Dave Attell]] embarked on their ''Bumping Mics'' comedy tour.<ref name=INTERROBANG3>{{cite web |url=https://theinterrobang.com/dave-attell-jeffrey-ross-two-giants-bumping-mics-tour/ |title=Dave Attell and Jeffrey Ross: Two Giants, Bumping Mics on Tour |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 1, 2018 |website=The Interrobang |publisher=Orange Pop Media |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Footage of their tour was also released in a three-part special on [[Netflix]].<ref name=UPI>{{cite news |last=Hooper |first=Ben |date=December 7, 2018 |title=Attell and Ross: 'Real hero' of 'Bumping Mics' is 'the punchline' |url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/TV/2018/12/07/Attell-and-Ross-Real-hero-of-Bumping-Mics-is-the-punchline/8331544123726/ |work=[[United Press International]] |location=Boca Raton, Florida, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> The ''Bumping Mics'' comedy special was filmed during three of their performances at the [[Comedy Cellar]] in New York City.<ref name=UPI/> Their shows consisted of [[observational humor|observational]] and [[political humor]] interspersed with Ross and Attell roasting one another as well as members of the audience.<ref name=DAILYFREEPRESS>{{cite news |last=Wiener |first=Sophie |date=November 30, 2018 |title=REVIEW: \u2018Bumping Mics with Jeff Ross and Dave Attell\u2019 is crude and mean, yet heartwarming |url=https://dailyfreepress.com/blog/2018/11/30/review-bumping-mics-with-jeff-ross-and-dave-attell-is-crude-and-mean-yet-heartwarming/ |work=[[The Daily Free Press]] |location=Boston, Massachusetts, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=INTERROBANG2>{{cite web |url=https://theinterrobang.com/bumping-mics-dave-attell-jeff-ross-jfl/ |title=Bumping Mics With Dave Attell and Jeff Ross at JFL |last=Dahms |first=Sara |date=July 27, 2017 |website=The Interrobang |publisher=Orange Pop Media |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> The comedians also invited audience members onto the stage, some of whom included [[Bob Saget]], [[Gilbert Gottfried]], [[Michael Che]], [[Amy Schumer]], [[Nikki Glaser]] and [[Paul Rudd]].<ref name=UPI/>\n\nStarting in 2019, [[Netflix]] began airing the series ''[[Historical Roasts]]'', where Ross hosts fictionalized versions of comedy roasts for figures like [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Anne Frank]].\n\n===Acting and voice work===\nOne of Ross's first acting roles was a small part in the 1996 comedy film ''[[Celtic Pride]]''.<ref name=HUFFPO>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/21/jeffrey-ross-at-occupy-la_n_1026084.html |title=Jeffrey Ross At Occupy LA: Part Stand Up, Part Soap Box |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 21, 2011 |website=[[The Huffington Post]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://uproxx.com/tv/jeff-ross-dressed-as-joe-paterno/ |title=Jeff Ross Went To Roseanne\u2019s Comedy Central Roast Dressed As Joe Paterno |last=Kurp |first=Josh |date=August 5, 2012 |website=[[Uproxx]] |publisher= |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Some of his other film roles include a security guard the film ''[[Stuck on You (2003 film)|Stuck on You]]'' (2003) and a wedding band leader in the film ''[[Along Came Polly]]'' (2004).<ref name=VARIETY2/><ref name=LAIST>{{cite news |last=H |first=Tim |date=April 22, 2010 |title=Seven Questions: Jeffrey Ross, Comedian/Author of I Only Roast the Ones I Love |url=https://laist.com/2010/04/22/seven_questions_jeffrey_ross_comedi.php |work=[[LAist]] |location=Los Angeles, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190505192835/https://laist.com/2010/04/22/seven_questions_jeffrey_ross_comedi.php |archive-date=May 5, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ross's television acting work includes roles on [[HBO]]'s ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]'' and ''[[Crashing (U.S. TV series)|Crashing]]'', and [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]''.<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/><ref>{{cite news |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=March 8, 2019 |title='Crashing' canceled after three seasons at HBO |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/tv/ct-ent-crashing-canceled-20190308-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |location=Chicago, Illinois, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> He also played a dramatic role on [[CBS]]'s ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]''.<ref name=VARIETY2/><ref name=MONTREALGAZ/>\n\nRoss was co-creator of the [[satire|satirical]] animated program ''[[Where My Dogs At?]]'' that was broadcast on [[MTV2]] in 2006. The series centers around characters Buddy, a [[beagle]] voiced by Ross, and Woof, a [[bulldog]] voiced by [[Tracy Morgan]].<ref name=IGN>{{cite web |url=https://ca.ign.com/articles/2006/06/06/jeffrey-ross-on-where-my-dogs-at |title=Jeffrey Ross on Where My Dogs At? |last=Zoromski |first=Brian |date=June 6, 2006 |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |location=San Francisco, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019 |quote=}}</ref> Ross has also voiced a characters on two episodes of the animated series ''[[Future-Worm!]]'' as well as on an episode of the [[live-action animated film|live-action/animated]] series ''[[Happy! (TV series)|Happy!]]''<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Flores |first=Terry |date=July 28, 2016 |title=Get to Know Ryan Quincy, Creator of Disney XD\u2019s New Series \u2018Future-Worm\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/comedy-central-jeff-ross-roast-battle-1201909718/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |location=Los Angeles, California, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/realjeffreyross/status/1121181826624581633 |title=@realjeffreyross |date=April 24, 2019 |website=Twitter |access-date=May 1, 2019 |quote=I play Pile Of Twigs and @pattonoswalt plays a unicorn named Happy on tonight\u2019s episode of \u201cHappy\u201d. Watch and enjoy 10pm on @SYFY if you\u2019re a dark fucked up person. #SeeHappy @happysyfy}}</ref> An animated version of Jeff Ross (voiced by Ross himself) appears in an episode of ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]'' that aired in 2012.<ref name=CITYPAGES>{{cite news |last=Strait |first=Patrick |date=January 31, 2012 |title=Jeff Ross talks Batman, losing his virginity, roasting Minnesota |url=http://www.citypages.com/arts/jeff-ross-talks-batman-losing-his-virginity-roasting-minnesota-6587278 |work=[[City Pages]] |location=Minneapolis, Minnesota, United States |access-date=May 1, 2019 }}</ref> During the episode his character attends a roast of [[Batman (comics)|Batman]].<ref name=CITYPAGES/>\n\n===Other appearances as himself===\nRoss appeared in the 2005 documentary ''[[The Aristocrats (film)|The Aristocrats]]'' about the famous [[The Aristocrats |dirty joke of the same name]].<ref name=LAIST/>\n\nHe was the guest on the debut episode of the ''[[WTF with Marc Maron]]'' podcast in 2009 and also appeared on the podcast's 800<sup>th</sup> episode in 2017.<ref name=LAWEEKLY/>\n\nRoss appeared in the third tournament of [[Celebrity Poker]] in 2004, but lost in his first match.<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/> He was also a competitor on the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 7)|seventh season]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'' that aired in 2008.<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/> During rehearsal for their first dance, his dancing partner [[Edyta \u015aliwi\u0144ska]] accidentally poked Ross in the eye, causing a scratched [[cornea]].<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/>  Against medical advice, Ross continued the competition, but the couple were the first to be eliminated.<ref name=MONTREALGAZ/>\n\nIn 2011 Ross visited the protesters of the [[Occupy movement]] in Los Angeles to support their cause.<ref name=HUFFPO/> He took to the microphone at a stage set-up at [[Los Angeles City Hall]].<ref name=HUFFPO/> His talk included roasting [[Wall Street]] and the [[Big_Four_(banking)#United_States|big banks]].<ref name=HUFFPO/>\n\nIn 2019, he appeared on an episode of \u2018\u2019[[Crank Yankers]]\u2019\u2019 as himself.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Celtic Pride]]''\n| Car Theft Victim\n| \n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Taxman (film)|Taxman]]''\n| Tax Collector\n| \n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Isn't She Great]]''\n| Shecky\n| \n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle (film)|The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle]]''\n| District Attorney\n| \n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[National Security (2003 film)|National Security]]''\n| Security Guard\n| \n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Stuck on You (film)|Stuck on You]]''\n| Beaze Security Guard\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Along Came Polly]]''\n| Wedding Band Leader\n| \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[American Dreamz]]''\n| Oscar\n| \n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Farce of the Penguins]]''\n| Funny-Looking Bastard (voice)\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[One, Two, Many]]''\n| Ernie\n| Direct-to-video\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[A Novel Romance]]''\n| Douglas Silver\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Wedding Ringer]]''\n| Hal Lane\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Flock of Dudes]]''\n| Masturbator\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Comedian (2016 film)|The Comedian]]''\n| \n| Writer\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Emoji Movie]]''\n| Internet Troll (voice)\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Dr. Katz, Professional Therapist]]''\n| Jeffrey (voice)\n| Episode: \"Blind Date\"\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Cosby]]''\n| Carl\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Shasta McNasty]]''\n| Bank Manager\n| Episode: \"True Size\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Greg the Bunny]]''\n| Security Guard\n| Episode: \"Welcome to Sweetknuckle Junction\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Six Feet Under (TV series)|Six Feet Under]]''\n| Shiva Comic\n| Episode: \"Back to the Garden\"\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]''\n| Dougie Max\n| Episode: \"Last Laugh\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]''\n| Billy\n| Episode: \"Dead in the Nethers\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Where My Dogs At?]]''\n| Buddy (voice)\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Sarah Silverman Program]]''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"Ah, Men\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Childrens Hospital]]''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"Joke Overload\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Big Time Rush]]''\n| Insult Comic\n| Episode: \"Big Time Guru\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| Episode: \"Crisis: 22,300 Miles Above Earth!\"\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| ''[[The Burn with Jeff Ross]]''\n| Himself\n| 12 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Drunk History]]''\n| [[Francis Scott Key]]\n| Episode: \"Baltimore\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| Episode: \"[[Clown in the Dumps]]\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|Comedy Bang! Bang!]]''\n| Himself \n| Episode: \"Amber Tamblyn Wears a Leather Jacket & Black Booties\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Grandfathered (TV series)|Grandfathered]]''\n| Marv\n| Episode: \"Some Guy I'm Seeing\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Dr. Ken]]''\n| Doug\n| Episode: \"Ken Tries Standup\"\n|-\n| 2016\u20132018\n| ''[[Jeff Ross Presents Roast Battle]]''\n| Himself\n| 19 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Future-Worm!]]''\n| Mr. Bleaker (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018\n| ''[[Crashing (American TV series)|Crashing]]''\n| Himself\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n| ''[[Rapunzel's Tangled Adventure]]''\n| Hook Foot\n| 24 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[American Dad!]]''\n| Chief Danny (voice)\n| Episode: \"Camp Campawanda\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Penn Zero: Part-Time Hero]]''\n| Sonny (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Teachers (2016 TV series)|Teachers]]''\n| Fire Marshal Brownstein\n| Episode: \"Toxic Workplace\"\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Sneaky Pete]]''\n| D.C. Doug\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Happy! (TV series)|Happy!]]''\n| Twigs (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Historical Roasts]]''\n| Himself\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Crank Yankers]]''\n| Himself (voice)\n| Episode: \"Jimmy Kimmel, Kathy Griffin & Jeff Ross\"\n|-\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n* ''No Offense'' (2008, [[Shout! Factory]]) - CD/DVD/Download\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jeff Ross}}\n*{{official website}}\n*{{IMDb name|743506|Jeff Ross}}\n* [https://archive.is/20100724224142/http://www.comedyhalloffame.com/archives/jeffrey-ross/ Jeff Ross] at Comedy Hall of Fame Archives\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ross, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:American comedy writers]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Communications alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American comedians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Democrats]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Springfield Township, Union County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:27b0:4a01:eb80:6127:9625:dcdf:e71c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Ross"}
{"title_page": "Julie Kavner", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Julie Kavner\n| image        = Julie Kavner 1974.JPG\n| caption      = Kavner in 1974\n| birth_name   = Julie Deborah Kavner\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1950|9|7}}\n| birth_place  = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| occupation  = Actress\n| years_active = 1973\u2013present\n| height        = 1.7 m\n| partner      = [[David Davis (TV producer)|David Davis]] (1976\u2013present)\n}}\n\n'''Julie Deborah Kavner''' (born September 7, 1950)<ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-06-15-ca-2655-story.html</ref> is an American actress. She first attracted notice for her role as Brenda Morgenstern, the younger sister of Valerie Harper's title character in the sitcom ''[[Rhoda]]'', for which she won a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress - Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]]. She is best known for her voice role as [[Marge Simpson]] on the animated television series ''[[The Simpsons]]''. She also voices other characters for the show, including Marge's mother, [[Simpson family#Jacqueline Bouvier|Jacqueline Bouvier]], and sisters [[Patty and Selma|Patty and Selma Bouvier]].\n\nKnown for her improvisation and distinctive \"honeyed gravel voice\",<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner was cast in her first professional acting role as [[Brenda Morgenstern]] in ''[[Rhoda]]'' in 1974. She received four [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations for playing the character, winning the award in 1978, the year that the series ended. Starting in 1987, Kavner started appearing on ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]''. ''The Tracey Ullman Show'' included a series of [[The Simpsons shorts|animated shorts]] about a dysfunctional family. Voices were needed for the shorts, and the producers asked Kavner to voice Marge. The shorts were spun off into ''The Simpsons''.\n\nKavner has been described as \"nearly reclusive\"; part of her contract says that she will never have to promote ''The Simpsons'' on video. For her work as Marge, Kavner received another [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Voice-Over Performance|Outstanding Voice-Over Performance]] in 1992 and an [[Annie Award]] nomination for her performance as the character in ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''.\n\nTypically cast as a \"woman who is supportive, sympathetic or self-effacingly funny\",<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner grew to dislike playing such roles. In 1992, she starred in ''[[This Is My Life (1992 film)|This Is My Life]]'', her first leading role in a feature film. Kavner has also appeared in live-action roles in six films written by [[Woody Allen]] and in the [[Adam Sandler]] comedy ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nKavner was born in Los Angeles, California, on September 7, 1950,<ref>{{cite news|title=Today in History - September 7|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/20468369|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=2007-09-07|accessdate=2009-02-13|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> the second daughter of Rose (1918\u20132010), a family counselor, and David Kavner (1917\u20132016), a furniture manufacturer,<ref name=\"darling\"/> and grew up in Southern California. Her family is [[Jewish]]. She decided to pursue a career in acting because \"There was nothing else I wanted to do, ever\".<ref name=\"darling\"/> She attended Beverly Hills High School (which she later admitted she hated), where she was \"something of a loner\", and unsuccessfully tried out for several plays.<ref name=\"darling\"/> [[John Ingle]], formerly the chairman of the Beverly Hills High School art department, later commented that Kavner was \"excellent at improvisation, but she wasn't an [[ingenue (stock character)|ingenue]] and not that castable at that age\".<ref name=\"darling\"/>\n\nAfter graduating from high school, Kavner attended San Diego State University and majored in drama, being cast in several productions including a role as [[Charlotte Corday]] in ''[[Marat/Sade]]'', becoming known for her improvisation and ability to do both comedy and drama. After graduating in 1971, she got a day job as a typist at the UCLA School of the Arts and Architecture.<ref name=\"darling\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nIn 1973, Kavner auditioned for a role as one of [[Rhoda Morgenstern]]'s sisters in ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]''. David Davis, producer of the show, had convinced her to audition for the part, but decided to cast another actress instead.<ref name=\"Boston\">{{Cite news|title=From sitcoms to films, Kavner is true to her characters|work=[[Boston Globe]]|author=Golden, Daniel|date=1991-06-30}}</ref> A year later, Rhoda Morgenstern became the leading character in a spin-off called ''[[Rhoda]]''. Kavner was cast in her first professional acting role as [[Brenda Morgenstern]], sister of the eponymous character.<ref name=\"darling\"/> ''Rhoda'' ran on CBS from September 9, 1974, to December 1978. She received four Primetime Emmy Award nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress - Comedy Series|Outstanding Continuing Performance by a Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]] for playing Brenda, winning in 1978.<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/award_history_search |title=Primetime Emmy Awards Advanced Search|publisher=Emmys.org|accessdate=2009-02-10}}</ref> She also received four [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/29391 |title=Julie Kavner |publisher=Hollywood Foreign Press Agency |accessdate=2009-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080830042711/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/29391 |archivedate=2008-08-30 }}</ref> In 1975, she received [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination for her starring role in the daytime special ''The Girl Who Couldn't Lose''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julie-kavner/bio/159366|title=Julie Kavner|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref>\n\nFollowing ''Rhoda'', Kavner had a guest appearance on ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]]''<ref name=\"Winding\">{{cite news|title=Kavner's long and winding Rhoda|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/621566|work=[[Toronto Star]]|date=2009-04-21|accessdate=2009-04-21|author=Salem, Rob}}</ref> and appeared in the 1985 comedy ''[[Bad Medicine (film)|Bad Medicine]]''<ref>{{Cite news|title='Bad Medicine' overdoses on bad jokes|date=1985-11-26|author=Christiansen, Richard|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> as well as the 1987 film ''[[Surrender (1987 film)|Surrender]]'', both of which were box office failures.<ref name=\"Lift\"/> She appeared in the television movies ''[[Revenge of the Stepford Wives]]'', ''No Other Love'' and ''A Fine Romance'', and shot a television pilot.<ref name=\"darling\"/> She also starred in several stage plays, including a play called ''It Had to Be You''<ref name=\"Lift\"/> at a dinner theater in Canada, ''Particular Friendships'' in New York City in 1981,<ref>{{cite news|title=Theater: 'Particular Friendships', A First Play|url=http://theater2.nytimes.com/mem/theater/treview.html?pagewanted=print&res=9F0CEFDC1539F932A35753C1A967948260|work=The New York Times|date=1981-10-01|accessdate=2009-02-13|author=Rich, Frank}}</ref> and ''Two for the Seesaw'', directed by [[Burt Reynolds]].<ref name=\"Lift\"/> [[Woody Allen]] first saw Kavner one night while he was watching ''Rhoda'' in the 1970s. He thought that she was remarkable and later offered her a role in his 1986 film ''[[Hannah and Her Sisters]]''.<ref name=\"Boston\"/> Kavner agreed, and credits Allen and the film with rejuvenating her career.<ref name=\"Lift\">{{Cite news|title=Coming into her own - Kavner's sagging career got needed lift from Allen films|work=[[Syracuse Herald-Journal]]|author=Vadeboncoeur, John E.|date=1992-03-19}}</ref>\n\nKavner was then cast as a sidekick to [[Tracey Ullman]] in ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]'', which debuted on Fox in 1987. Kavner described the show as, \"like being back in school, a chance to play a wide variety of characters, some really vicious people, to not rest on laurels, to not play it safe\".<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner commented, \"What I do is not mimicry or an impersonation, but more of an assimilation. [On ''The Tracey Ullman Show''] we did a lot of looking at people to find out who<!-- sic --> to base our characters on. We did our homework on our lunch hour.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/> She received four Primetime Emmy Award nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program|Best Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program]].<ref name=\"emmys\"/>\n\n===''The Simpsons''===\n[[File:Julie Kavner.jpg|right|upright|thumb|Kavner in 2009]]\nKavner became most famous for her role as [[Marge Simpson]] on the animated television show ''[[The Simpsons]]'', a show that continues to the present. ''The Tracey Ullman Show'' included [[The Simpsons shorts|a series of animated shorts]] about the dysfunctional Simpson family. Voices were needed for the shorts, so the producers decided to ask Kavner and fellow cast member [[Dan Castellaneta]] to voice Marge and Homer rather than hire more actors.<ref name=\"The Age\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/02/27/1046064146568.html|title=D'oh, you're the voices|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2003-02-27|author=Lee, Luaine|newspaper=[[The Age]] | location=Melbourne}}</ref><ref name=\"FN\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,129665,00.html|title=D'oh!: The Voice of Homer Is Deceivingly Deadpan|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2008-08-18|author=Elber, Lynn|agency=Associated Press|work=Fox News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703090128/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0%2C2933%2C129665%2C00.html|archive-date=July 3, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kavner has what Hilary de Vries of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described as a \"honeyed gravel voice\".<ref name=\"darling\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CEFDF1F38F935A15752C0A964958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=1|title='Darling! Listen to Me'|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=1992-01-26|author=De Vries, Hilary|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Kavner says her distinctive voice is due to \"a bump on [her] vocal cords\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The actress with the one-of-a-kind voice stars in Nora Ephron's comedy 'This is my Life'.|date=1992-03-13|work=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|author=Haun, Harry}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Marge is her most famous character, Kavner's favorite characters to voice are Marge's sisters [[Patty and Selma|Patty and Selma Bouvier]] because \"they're really funny and sad at the same time\".<ref name=\"Hamilton\">{{cite news|title=Ay caramba!: Only TV could call this work|date=1996-12-31|work=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|author=Duffy, Mike}}</ref> Series creator [[Matt Groening]] instructed Kavner to voice the duo as characters who \"suck the life out of everything\".<ref>Groening, Matt. (2001). Commentary for \"[[Simpsons Roasting on an Open Fire]]\", in ''The Simpsons: The Complete First Season'' [DVD]. 20th Century Fox.</ref> Both have similar raspy voices, but Patty's voice is more masculine and has a lower register, while Selma's voice is a little sweeter.<ref name=\"Jean\">Jean, Al. (2004). Commentary for \"[[Selma's Choice]]\", in ''The Simpsons: The Complete Fourth Season'' [DVD]. 20th Century Fox.</ref> Kavner also provides the voices of every other female member of the Bouvier family, including Marge's mother [[Jaqueline Bouvier|Jacqueline]], Great-Aunt Gladys (a dead relative who was introduced on season four's \"[[Selma's Choice]]\"), and an unnamed grandmother seen on the season six episode \"[[Fear of Flying (The Simpsons)|Fear of Flying]]\".<ref name=\"Jean\"/>\n\nPart of Kavner's contract says that she will never have to promote ''The Simpsons'' on video and she rarely performs Marge's voice in public because she believes it \"destroys the illusion. People feel these are real people.\"<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/><ref name=\"Sheridan\">{{cite news|title=Meet the Simpsons|date=2004-05-06|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Daily Express]]|author=Sheridan, Peter}}</ref> Kavner takes recording sessions seriously, and feels that voice acting is \"a little more limiting than live acting. And I have nothing to do with my character's movement.\"<ref name=\"Water\">{{cite news|title=Treading 'Water' Julie Kavner takes break from Marge Simpson to star in Woody Allen's TV Movie |date=1994-09-18|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|author=Weiskind, Ron}}</ref> [[Nancy Cartwright]], who voices [[Bart Simpson]], said in her book ''[[My Life as a 10-Year-Old Boy]]'' that Kavner is \"a workhorse of an actor\" with \"extraordinary professionalism and quiet work ethic\", and notes that she is rarely late for recording sessions.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cartwright|first=Nancy|title=[[My Life as a 10-Year-Old Boy]]|year=2000|publisher=[[Hyperion (publisher)|Hyperion]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/mylifeastenyearo00nanc/page/48 48]|location=New York City|isbn=0-7868-8600-5}}</ref>\n\nUntil 1998, Kavner was paid $30,000 per episode. During a pay dispute in 1998, Fox threatened to replace the six main voice actors with new actors, going as far as preparing to cast new voices.<ref name=Glaister/> However, the dispute was soon resolved and she received $125,000 per episode until 2004 when the voice actors demanded that they be paid $360,000 an episode.<ref name=Glaister>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/04/02/1080544690429.html|title=Simpsons actors demand bigger share|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2004-04-03|author=Glaister, Dan|newspaper=The Age | location=Melbourne}}</ref> The issue was resolved a month later,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/05/01/entertainment/main615066.shtml|title='Simpsons' Cast Goes Back To Work|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2004-05-01|publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> and Kavner earned $250,000 per episode.<ref name=\"Sheridan\"/> After salary re-negotiations in 2008, the voice actors received approximately $400,000 per episode.<ref>{{cite news | title = Simpsons cast sign new pay deal | work = BBC News | date = 2008-06-03 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7434296.stm | accessdate=2009-02-10}}</ref> Three years later, with Fox threatening to cancel the series unless production costs were cut, Kavner and the other cast members accepted a 30 percent pay cut, down to just over $300,000 per episode.<ref>{{cite news|last=Block|first=Alex Ben|title='The Simpsons' Renewed for Two More Seasons|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/simpsons-renewed-two-more-seasons-245748|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 15, 2011|date=October 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[44th Primetime Emmy Awards]], Kavner received a Primetime Emmy Award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Voice-Over Performance|Outstanding Voice-Over Performance]] for voicing Marge in the [[The Simpsons (season 3)|season three]] episode \"[[I Married Marge]]\".<ref name=\"emmys\"/> In 2004, Kavner and Dan Castellaneta won a [[Young Artist Award]] for Most Popular Mom & Dad in a TV Series.<ref name=\"YAA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms25.htm |title=25th Annual Winners and Nominees |accessdate=2009-02-10 |publisher=Youngartistawards.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817061116/http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms25.htm |archivedate=2016-08-17 }}</ref> For her performance in ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'', Kavner was nominated for Best Voice Acting in an Animated Feature at the 2007 [[Annie Awards]], but [[Ian Holm]] from ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]'' received the award.<ref name=\"A35\">{{cite news|url=http://annieawards.org/foryourconsideration.html |title=For Your Consideration |accessdate=2009-02-10 |date=2007-12-31 |publisher=Annie Awards |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217224351/http://annieawards.org/foryourconsideration.html |archivedate=2009-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/awardcentral_article/VR1117980588.html?nav=news&categoryid=1983&cs=1|title='Ratatouille' nearly sweeps Annies|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2008-02-08|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Debruge, Peter}}</ref> Kavner's emotional performance in the movie got positive reviews, and one critic said she \"gave what must be the most heartfelt performance ever to find its way into a movie based on an irreverent cartoon\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/arts_entertainment/film.php?ak=2879 |title=Homer's Odyssey |publisher=Metro Weekly |accessdate=2009-02-10 |date=2007-07-26 |author=Shulman, Randy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926231021/http://www.metroweekly.com/arts_entertainment/film.php?ak=2879 |archivedate=2007-09-26 }}</ref> Some scenes in the movie, such as Marge's emotional video message to Homer, were recorded over 100 times, leaving Kavner exhausted.<ref name=moviesonline>{{cite news|url=http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_12524.html |title=The Simpsons Movie Interviews |author=Roberts, Sheila |accessdate=2009-02-10 |publisher=Movies Online |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104132905/http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_12524.html |archivedate=2009-01-04 }}</ref>\n\n===Further career===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Julie Kavner - This is my life.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Kavner's portrayal of Dottie Ingels in ''[[This Is My Life (1992 film)|This Is My Life]]'' was her first leading role in a feature film.]] -->\nMany of Kavner's roles have been described by ''New York Times'' writer Hilary de Vries as a \"woman who is supportive, sympathetic, or self-effacingly funny\".<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner grew to despise playing such roles, saying \"If it smacks of Brenda Morgenstern, I won't take the job.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/> She had a supporting role as Eleanor Costello, a nurse who befriends [[Robin Williams]]' character in the [[Academy Award]] nominated film ''[[Awakenings]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Awakenings |url=http://www.variety.com/profiles/Film/main/24664/Awakenings.html?dataSet=1 |work=Variety |accessdate=2009-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724205645/http://www.variety.com/profiles/Film/main/24664/Awakenings.html?dataSet=1 |archivedate=July 24, 2009 }}</ref> Kavner interviewed several nurses in preparation for the role, and [[Penny Marshall]], the director of the film, described Kavner as \"a low-maintenance actor [...] You never have to worry about giving [her] back-story for her characters.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/> In 1992, Kavner starred in ''[[This Is My Life (1992 film)|This Is My Life]]'', her first leading role in a feature film. Kavner played Dottie Ingels, an aspiring [[stand-up comedian]] who starts neglecting her family when her career begins to take off. Kavner described Dottie as \"really selfish\" but admitted, \"I liked the role for that very reason.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner had been asked to play a character with a smaller role in the film, but [[Joe Roth]], at the time the chairman of [[20th Century Fox]], suggested that they cast a lesser known actress in the lead role.<ref name=\"darling\"/> [[Nora Ephron]], the writer of ''This Is My Life'', said Kavner \"has so little vanity that it is almost shocking. Not only does she have no demands as an actress - 'How big is my trailer, what's in my refrigerator?' - but she will do anything for the character if it makes sense to her.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/>\n\nKavner has frequently appeared in [[Woody Allen]] films, having roles in ''Hannah and Her Sisters'' (1986), ''[[Radio Days]]'' (1987), ''[[New York Stories]]'' (1989), ''[[Alice (1990 film)|Alice]]'' (1990), ''[[Shadows and Fog]]'' (1991), the television movie ''[[Don't Drink the Water (1994 film)|Don't Drink the Water]]'' (1994)<ref name=\"FoxFlash\"/> and ''[[Deconstructing Harry]]'' (1997).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117329532?refcatid=31|title=Deconstructing Harry|author=Stratton, David|date=1997-09-07|accessdate=2009-02-13|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> Allen described her as \"a naturally funny person. When she does a scene, you listen to her and look at her, and the prism through which it's all filtered is funny.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=The choicest of voices |author=Diamond, Jamie|work=[[Calgary Herald]]|date=1991-01-19}}</ref> Kavner believes he is \"a true filmmaker, one that has something to say, continually experimenting on different themes within his own film-making\", adding that \"anything [Allen] ever does, I always want to do, [...] I don't even have to read it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=Julie Kavner would follow Woody anywhere, even to the difficult medium of TV| work=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]|date=1994-12-17}}</ref>\n\nShe has done voice-over work in films such as ''[[The Lion King 1\u00bd]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=The Lion King 1\u00bd|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117923053?refCatId=1023|work=Variety|author=Leydon, Joe|date=2004-02-11}}</ref> ''[[Dr. Dolittle (1998 film)|Dr. Dolittle]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117477646?refcatid=31|title=Dr. Dolittle|author=Klady, Leonard|work=Variety|date=1998-06-24|accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref> and an uncredited role as an announcer in ''[[A Walk on the Moon]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117491901?refcatid=31|title=A Walk on the Moon|author=Lovell, Glenn|date=1999-03-09|accessdate=2009-02-13|work=Variety}}</ref> Her most recent live-action film was a role of the mother of [[Adam Sandler]]'s character in ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Man-Child Who Has His World Under Control in 'Click'|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2006/06/23/movies/23clic.html|author=Dargis, Manohla|date=2006-06-23|accessdate=2009-02-13|work=The New York Times}}</ref> She also worked with Tracey Ullman in the HBO sketch comedy series ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]''.<ref name=\"FoxFlash\">{{cite web|title=Julie Kavner |url=http://www.foxflash.com/div.php/main/page?aID=1z2z2z175z13z4&bioid=1672 |publisher=FoxFlash |accessdate=2009-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929001926/http://www.foxflash.com/div.php/main/page?aID=1z2z2z175z13z4&bioid=1672 |archivedate=2011-09-29 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKavner leads a private, \"nearly reclusive\" life, \"discreet and guarded beyond the usual reticent star routine\".<ref name=\"darling\"/> She rarely makes public appearances and refuses to allow herself to be photographed at work, especially in the studio while doing ''The Simpsons''.<ref name=\"Winding\"/> Her partner is retired producer [[David Davis (TV producer)|David Davis]]; they have lived together since 1976.<ref name=\"Boston\"/><ref name=\"Winding\"/> In 1983, it was reported in ''[[Current Biography]]'' that Kavner is an avid athlete and a [[Pescetarianism|pescatarian]].<ref>''[[Current Biography Yearbook]], Volume 53''. (1992). H. W. Wilson Co. p. 318. \"Largely indifferent to food, Kavner generally follows a vegetarian diet, although she occasionally eats fish.\"</ref> In a 1992 interview with ''The New York Times'', Kavner said she was considering retiring, \"except for doing three days a year for Woody [Allen]\", but felt that if she did retire, she would receive a script she wanted \"to do more than life itself\".<ref name=\"darling\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[National Lampoon's Movie Madness]]''\n| Mrs. Falcone\n| \n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Bad Medicine (film)|Bad Medicine]]''\n| Cookie Katz\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Hannah and Her Sisters]]''\n| Gail\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Radio Days]]''\n| Mother\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Surrender (1987 film)|Surrender]]''\n| Ronnie\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[New York Stories]]''\n| Treva\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Awakenings]]''\n| Eleanor Costello\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Alice (1990 film)|Alice]]''\n| Decorator\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Shadows and Fog]]''\n| Alma\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[This Is My Life (1992 film)|This Is My Life]]''\n| Dottie Ingels\n| \n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[I'll Do Anything]]''\n| Nan Mulhanney\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Forget Paris]]''\n| Lucy\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Deconstructing Harry]]''\n| Grace\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Dr. Dolittle (1998 film)|Dr. Dolittle]]''\n| Female pigeon (voice)\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[Judy Berlin]]''\n| Marie\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[A Walk on the Moon]]''\n| P.A. Announcer\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Story of a Bad Boy''\n| Elaine\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Someone like You (film)|Someone like You]]''\n| Furry animal\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Barn Red''\n| Unnamed character\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[The Lion King 1\u00bd]]''\n| Ma (voice)\n| Direct-to-DVD \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]''\n| Trudy Newman\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''\n| [[Marge Simpson]], [[Patty and Selma|Patty and Selma Bouvier]] (voices)\n| Nominated - [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Annie Award for Voice Acting by a\nFemale Performer in an Animated Feature Production]]\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1974\u20131978\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n|110 episodes\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[The ABC Afternoon Playbreak]]''\n| Jane Darwin\n| Episode: \"The Girl Who Couldn't Lose\"\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Katherine (film)|Katherine]]''\n| Margot Weiss Goldman\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Petrocelli]]''\n| Julie\n| Episode: \"To See No Evil\"\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Bert D'Angelo/Superstar]]''\n| Billy Gordon\n| Episode: \"The Brown Horse Connection\"\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]''\n| Alice\n| Episode: \"Housewarming\"\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''No Other Love''\n| Janet Michaels\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Revenge of the Stepford Wives]]''\n| Megan Brady\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]]''\n| Monica Banta Douglas\n| Episode: \"Tony's Sister and Jim\"\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''A Fine Romance''\n| Laura Prescott\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1987\u20131990\n| ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]''\n| Various characters\n| 43 episodes\n|-\n| 1989\u2013present\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| [[Marge Simpson]], [[Patty and Selma|Patty and Selma Bouvier]], additional voices\n| Main role\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[42nd Primetime Emmy Awards]]''\n| Marge Simpson (voice)\n| Television special\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Sibs]]''\n| Julia\n| Episode: \"Honey, I Shrunk My Head\"\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''To the Moon, Alice''\n| Sitcom Producer\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Birdland (TV series)|Birdland]]''\n| Madeline Diamond\n| Episode: \"Grand Delusion\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Don't Drink the Water (1994 film)|Don't Drink the Water]]''\n| Marion Hollander\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Jake's Women]]''\n| Karen\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1996\u20131999\n| ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]''\n| Various characters\n| 14 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Marge Simpson, [[Patty and Selma|Patty and Selma Bouvier]] (voice)\n| Episode: \"[[The Simpsons Guy]]\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''\n| Marge Simpson (voice)\n| Episode: \"Final Show\"\n|-\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n*''[[The Simpsons (arcade game)|The Simpsons]]'' (1991) - Marge Simpson\n*''[[Storybook Weaver]]'' (1994) - Mayzie Bird\n*''[[The Simpsons Cartoon Studio]]'' (1996) - Marge Simpson\n*''[[Virtual Springfield]]'' (1997) - Marge Simpson, Patty Bouvier, Selma Bouvier\n*''[[Simpsons Bowling]]'' (1999) - Marge Simpson, Patty Bouvier, Selma Bouvier\n*''[[The Simpsons Wrestling]]'' (2001) - Marge Simpson\n*''[[The Simpsons: Road Rage]]'' (2001) - Marge Simpson\n*''[[The Simpsons Skateboarding]]'' (2002) - Marge Simpson\n*''[[The Simpsons: Hit & Run]]'' (2003) - Marge Simpson, Patty Bouvier, Selma Bouvier\n*''[[Storybook Weaver|Storybook Weaver Deluxe]]'' (2004) - Mayzie Bird\n*''[[The Simpsons Game]]'' (2007) - Marge Simpson, Patty Bouvier, Selma Bouvier\n*''[[The Simpsons: Tapped Out]]'' (2012) - Marge Simpson, Patty Bouvier, Selma Bouvier\n\n===Music video===\n*\"[[Do the Bartman]]\" (1990) - Marge Simpson\n\n===Theme park===\n*''[[The Simpsons Ride]]'' (2008) - Marge Simpson, Patty Bouvier, Selma Bouvier\n\n==Awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Award\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Category\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Role\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Series/film\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Result\n|-\n| [[27th Primetime Emmy Awards|1975]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]]\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[32nd Golden Globe Awards|1975]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Television]]\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[2nd Daytime Emmy Awards|1975]]\n| [[Daytime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| Outstanding Actress in a Daytime Drama Special\n| Jane Darwin\n| ''The Girl Who Couldn't Lose''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[28th Primetime Emmy Awards|1976]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]]\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[33rd Golden Globe Awards|1976]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Television]]\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[29th Primetime Emmy Awards|1977]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]]\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[34th Golden Globe Awards|1977]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Television]]\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[30th Primetime Emmy Awards|1978]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]]\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[35th Golden Globe Awards|1978]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Television Actress in a Supporting Role]]\n| Brenda Morgenstern\n| ''[[Rhoda]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[39th Primetime Emmy Awards|1987]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program|Outstanding Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program]]\n| Various\n| ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[40th Primetime Emmy Awards|1988]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program|Outstanding Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program]]\n| Various\n| ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[41st Primetime Emmy Awards|1989]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program|Outstanding Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program]]\n| Various\n| ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[42nd Primetime Emmy Awards|1990]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program|Outstanding Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program]]\n| Various\n| ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[44th Primetime Emmy Awards|1992]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Voice-Over Performance|Outstanding Voice-Over Performance]]\n| [[Marge Simpson]]\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]'': \"[[I Married Marge]]\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[26th Young Artist Awards|2004]]\n| [[Young Artist Award]]\n| Most Popular Mom & Pop in a Television Series\n| [[Marge Simpson]]\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[35th Annie Awards|2008]]\n| [[Annie Award]]\n| [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Voice Acting in an Animated Feature Production]]\n| [[Marge Simpson]]\n| ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|1413}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=99323|name=Julie Kavner}}\n* {{iobdb name|3618}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Julie Kavner\n| list =\n{{EmmyAward ComedySupportingActress 1976-2000}}\n{{EmmyAward VoiceOver 1990-2000}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kavner, Julie}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American video game actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:San Diego State University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Julie Kavner\n| image        = Julie Kavner 1974.JPG\n| caption      = Kavner in 1974\n| birth_name   = Julie Deborah Kavner\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1950|9|7}}\n| birth_place  = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| occupation  = Actress\n| years_active = 1973\u2013present\n| partner      = [[David Davis (TV producer)|David Davis]] (1976\u2013present)\n}}\n\n'''Julie Deborah Kavner''' (born September 7, 1950)<ref>https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-06-15-ca-2655-story.html</ref> is an American actress. She first attracted notice for her role as Brenda Morgenstern, the younger sister of Valerie Harper's title character in the sitcom ''[[Rhoda]]'', for which she won a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress - Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]]. She is best known for her voice role as [[Marge Simpson]] on the animated television series ''[[The Simpsons]]''. She also voices other characters for the show, including Marge's mother, [[Simpson family#Jacqueline Bouvier|Jacqueline Bouvier]], and sisters [[Patty and Selma|Patty and Selma Bouvier]].\n\nKnown for her improvisation and distinctive \"honeyed gravel voice\",<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner was cast in her first professional acting role as [[Brenda Morgenstern]] in ''[[Rhoda]]'' in 1974. She received four [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations for playing the character, winning the award in 1978, the year that the series ended. Starting in 1987, Kavner started appearing on ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]''. ''The Tracey Ullman Show'' included a series of [[The Simpsons shorts|animated shorts]] about a dysfunctional family. Voices were needed for the shorts, and the producers asked Kavner to voice Marge. The shorts were spun off into ''The Simpsons''.\n\nKavner has been described as \"nearly reclusive\"; part of her contract says that she will never have to promote ''The Simpsons'' on video. For her work as Marge, Kavner received another [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Voice-Over Performance|Outstanding Voice-Over Performance]] in 1992 and an [[Annie Award]] nomination for her performance as the character in ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''.\n\nTypically cast as a \"woman who is supportive, sympathetic or self-effacingly funny\",<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner grew to dislike playing such roles. In 1992, she starred in ''[[This Is My Life (1992 film)|This Is My Life]]'', her first leading role in a feature film. Kavner has also appeared in live-action roles in six films written by [[Woody Allen]] and in the [[Adam Sandler]] comedy ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nKavner was born in Los Angeles, California, on September 7, 1950,<ref>{{cite news|title=Today in History - September 7|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/20468369|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=2007-09-07|accessdate=2009-02-13|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> the second daughter of Rose (1918\u20132010), a family counselor, and David Kavner (1917\u20132016), a furniture manufacturer,<ref name=\"darling\"/> and grew up in Southern California. Her family is [[Jewish]]. She decided to pursue a career in acting because \"There was nothing else I wanted to do, ever\".<ref name=\"darling\"/> She attended Beverly Hills High School (which she later admitted she hated), where she was \"something of a loner\", and unsuccessfully tried out for several plays.<ref name=\"darling\"/> [[John Ingle]], formerly the chairman of the Beverly Hills High School art department, later commented that Kavner was \"excellent at improvisation, but she wasn't an [[ingenue (stock character)|ingenue]] and not that castable at that age\".<ref name=\"darling\"/>\n\nAfter graduating from high school, Kavner attended San Diego State University and majored in drama, being cast in several productions including a role as [[Charlotte Corday]] in ''[[Marat/Sade]]'', becoming known for her improvisation and ability to do both comedy and drama. After graduating in 1971, she got a day job as a typist at the UCLA School of the Arts and Architecture.<ref name=\"darling\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nIn 1973, Kavner auditioned for a role as one of [[Rhoda Morgenstern]]'s sisters in ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]''. David Davis, producer of the show, had convinced her to audition for the part, but decided to cast another actress instead.<ref name=\"Boston\">{{Cite news|title=From sitcoms to films, Kavner is true to her characters|work=[[Boston Globe]]|author=Golden, Daniel|date=1991-06-30}}</ref> A year later, Rhoda Morgenstern became the leading character in a spin-off called ''[[Rhoda]]''. Kavner was cast in her first professional acting role as [[Brenda Morgenstern]], sister of the eponymous character.<ref name=\"darling\"/> ''Rhoda'' ran on CBS from September 9, 1974, to December 1978. She received four Primetime Emmy Award nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress - Comedy Series|Outstanding Continuing Performance by a Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]] for playing Brenda, winning in 1978.<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/award_history_search |title=Primetime Emmy Awards Advanced Search|publisher=Emmys.org|accessdate=2009-02-10}}</ref> She also received four [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/29391 |title=Julie Kavner |publisher=Hollywood Foreign Press Agency |accessdate=2009-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080830042711/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/member/29391 |archivedate=2008-08-30 }}</ref> In 1975, she received [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nomination for her starring role in the daytime special ''The Girl Who Couldn't Lose''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/julie-kavner/bio/159366|title=Julie Kavner|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref>\n\nFollowing ''Rhoda'', Kavner had a guest appearance on ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]]''<ref name=\"Winding\">{{cite news|title=Kavner's long and winding Rhoda|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/621566|work=[[Toronto Star]]|date=2009-04-21|accessdate=2009-04-21|author=Salem, Rob}}</ref> and appeared in the 1985 comedy ''[[Bad Medicine (film)|Bad Medicine]]''<ref>{{Cite news|title='Bad Medicine' overdoses on bad jokes|date=1985-11-26|author=Christiansen, Richard|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> as well as the 1987 film ''[[Surrender (1987 film)|Surrender]]'', both of which were box office failures.<ref name=\"Lift\"/> She appeared in the television movies ''[[Revenge of the Stepford Wives]]'', ''No Other Love'' and ''A Fine Romance'', and shot a television pilot.<ref name=\"darling\"/> She also starred in several stage plays, including a play called ''It Had to Be You''<ref name=\"Lift\"/> at a dinner theater in Canada, ''Particular Friendships'' in New York City in 1981,<ref>{{cite news|title=Theater: 'Particular Friendships', A First Play|url=http://theater2.nytimes.com/mem/theater/treview.html?pagewanted=print&res=9F0CEFDC1539F932A35753C1A967948260|work=The New York Times|date=1981-10-01|accessdate=2009-02-13|author=Rich, Frank}}</ref> and ''Two for the Seesaw'', directed by [[Burt Reynolds]].<ref name=\"Lift\"/> [[Woody Allen]] first saw Kavner one night while he was watching ''Rhoda'' in the 1970s. He thought that she was remarkable and later offered her a role in his 1986 film ''[[Hannah and Her Sisters]]''.<ref name=\"Boston\"/> Kavner agreed, and credits Allen and the film with rejuvenating her career.<ref name=\"Lift\">{{Cite news|title=Coming into her own - Kavner's sagging career got needed lift from Allen films|work=[[Syracuse Herald-Journal]]|author=Vadeboncoeur, John E.|date=1992-03-19}}</ref>\n\nKavner was then cast as a sidekick to [[Tracey Ullman]] in ''[[The Tracey Ullman Show]]'', which debuted on Fox in 1987. Kavner described the show as, \"like being back in school, a chance to play a wide variety of characters, some really vicious people, to not rest on laurels, to not play it safe\".<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner commented, \"What I do is not mimicry or an impersonation, but more of an assimilation. [On ''The Tracey Ullman Show''] we did a lot of looking at people to find out who<!-- sic --> to base our characters on. We did our homework on our lunch hour.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/> She received four Primetime Emmy Award nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program|Best Individual Performance in a Variety or Music Program]].<ref name=\"emmys\"/>\n\n===''The Simpsons''===\n[[File:Julie Kavner.jpg|right|upright|thumb|Kavner in 2009]]\nKavner became most famous for her role as [[Marge Simpson]] on the animated television show ''[[The Simpsons]]'', a show that continues to the present. ''The Tracey Ullman Show'' included [[The Simpsons shorts|a series of animated shorts]] about the dysfunctional Simpson family. Voices were needed for the shorts, so the producers decided to ask Kavner and fellow cast member [[Dan Castellaneta]] to voice Marge and Homer rather than hire more actors.<ref name=\"The Age\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/02/27/1046064146568.html|title=D'oh, you're the voices|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2003-02-27|author=Lee, Luaine|newspaper=[[The Age]] | location=Melbourne}}</ref><ref name=\"FN\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,129665,00.html|title=D'oh!: The Voice of Homer Is Deceivingly Deadpan|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2008-08-18|author=Elber, Lynn|agency=Associated Press|work=Fox News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703090128/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0%2C2933%2C129665%2C00.html|archive-date=July 3, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kavner has what Hilary de Vries of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described as a \"honeyed gravel voice\".<ref name=\"darling\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CEFDF1F38F935A15752C0A964958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=1|title='Darling! Listen to Me'|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=1992-01-26|author=De Vries, Hilary|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Kavner says her distinctive voice is due to \"a bump on [her] vocal cords\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The actress with the one-of-a-kind voice stars in Nora Ephron's comedy 'This is my Life'.|date=1992-03-13|work=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|author=Haun, Harry}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Marge is her most famous character, Kavner's favorite characters to voice are Marge's sisters [[Patty and Selma|Patty and Selma Bouvier]] because \"they're really funny and sad at the same time\".<ref name=\"Hamilton\">{{cite news|title=Ay caramba!: Only TV could call this work|date=1996-12-31|work=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|author=Duffy, Mike}}</ref> Series creator [[Matt Groening]] instructed Kavner to voice the duo as characters who \"suck the life out of everything\".<ref>Groening, Matt. (2001). Commentary for \"[[Simpsons Roasting on an Open Fire]]\", in ''The Simpsons: The Complete First Season'' [DVD]. 20th Century Fox.</ref> Both have similar raspy voices, but Patty's voice is more masculine and has a lower register, while Selma's voice is a little sweeter.<ref name=\"Jean\">Jean, Al. (2004). Commentary for \"[[Selma's Choice]]\", in ''The Simpsons: The Complete Fourth Season'' [DVD]. 20th Century Fox.</ref> Kavner also provides the voices of every other female member of the Bouvier family, including Marge's mother [[Jaqueline Bouvier|Jacqueline]], Great-Aunt Gladys (a dead relative who was introduced on season four's \"[[Selma's Choice]]\"), and an unnamed grandmother seen on the season six episode \"[[Fear of Flying (The Simpsons)|Fear of Flying]]\".<ref name=\"Jean\"/>\n\nPart of Kavner's contract says that she will never have to promote ''The Simpsons'' on video and she rarely performs Marge's voice in public because she believes it \"destroys the illusion. People feel these are real people.\"<ref name=\"Hamilton\"/><ref name=\"Sheridan\">{{cite news|title=Meet the Simpsons|date=2004-05-06|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Daily Express]]|author=Sheridan, Peter}}</ref> Kavner takes recording sessions seriously, and feels that voice acting is \"a little more limiting than live acting. And I have nothing to do with my character's movement.\"<ref name=\"Water\">{{cite news|title=Treading 'Water' Julie Kavner takes break from Marge Simpson to star in Woody Allen's TV Movie |date=1994-09-18|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|author=Weiskind, Ron}}</ref> [[Nancy Cartwright]], who voices [[Bart Simpson]], said in her book ''[[My Life as a 10-Year-Old Boy]]'' that Kavner is \"a workhorse of an actor\" with \"extraordinary professionalism and quiet work ethic\", and notes that she is rarely late for recording sessions.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cartwright|first=Nancy|title=[[My Life as a 10-Year-Old Boy]]|year=2000|publisher=[[Hyperion (publisher)|Hyperion]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/mylifeastenyearo00nanc/page/48 48]|location=New York City|isbn=0-7868-8600-5}}</ref>\n\nUntil 1998, Kavner was paid $30,000 per episode. During a pay dispute in 1998, Fox threatened to replace the six main voice actors with new actors, going as far as preparing to cast new voices.<ref name=Glaister/> However, the dispute was soon resolved and she received $125,000 per episode until 2004 when the voice actors demanded that they be paid $360,000 an episode.<ref name=Glaister>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/04/02/1080544690429.html|title=Simpsons actors demand bigger share|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2004-04-03|author=Glaister, Dan|newspaper=The Age | location=Melbourne}}</ref> The issue was resolved a month later,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/05/01/entertainment/main615066.shtml|title='Simpsons' Cast Goes Back To Work|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2004-05-01|publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref> and Kavner earned $250,000 per episode.<ref name=\"Sheridan\"/> After salary re-negotiations in 2008, the voice actors received approximately $400,000 per episode.<ref>{{cite news | title = Simpsons cast sign new pay deal | work = BBC News | date = 2008-06-03 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7434296.stm | accessdate=2009-02-10}}</ref> Three years later, with Fox threatening to cancel the series unless production costs were cut, Kavner and the other cast members accepted a 30 percent pay cut, down to just over $300,000 per episode.<ref>{{cite news|last=Block|first=Alex Ben|title='The Simpsons' Renewed for Two More Seasons|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/simpsons-renewed-two-more-seasons-245748|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 15, 2011|date=October 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[44th Primetime Emmy Awards]], Kavner received a Primetime Emmy Award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Voice-Over Performance|Outstanding Voice-Over Performance]] for voicing Marge in the [[The Simpsons (season 3)|season three]] episode \"[[I Married Marge]]\".<ref name=\"emmys\"/> In 2004, Kavner and Dan Castellaneta won a [[Young Artist Award]] for Most Popular Mom & Dad in a TV Series.<ref name=\"YAA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms25.htm |title=25th Annual Winners and Nominees |accessdate=2009-02-10 |publisher=Youngartistawards.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817061116/http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms25.htm |archivedate=2016-08-17 }}</ref> For her performance in ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'', Kavner was nominated for Best Voice Acting in an Animated Feature at the 2007 [[Annie Awards]], but [[Ian Holm]] from ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]'' received the award.<ref name=\"A35\">{{cite news|url=http://annieawards.org/foryourconsideration.html |title=For Your Consideration |accessdate=2009-02-10 |date=2007-12-31 |publisher=Annie Awards |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217224351/http://annieawards.org/foryourconsideration.html |archivedate=2009-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/awardcentral_article/VR1117980588.html?nav=news&categoryid=1983&cs=1|title='Ratatouille' nearly sweeps Annies|accessdate=2009-02-10|date=2008-02-08|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Debruge, Peter}}</ref> Kavner's emotional performance in the movie got positive reviews, and one critic said she \"gave what must be the most heartfelt performance ever to find its way into a movie based on an irreverent cartoon\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/arts_entertainment/film.php?ak=2879 |title=Homer's Odyssey |publisher=Metro Weekly |accessdate=2009-02-10 |date=2007-07-26 |author=Shulman, Randy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926231021/http://www.metroweekly.com/arts_entertainment/film.php?ak=2879 |archivedate=2007-09-26 }}</ref> Some scenes in the movie, such as Marge's emotional video message to Homer, were recorded over 100 times, leaving Kavner exhausted.<ref name=moviesonline>{{cite news|url=http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_12524.html |title=The Simpsons Movie Interviews |author=Roberts, Sheila |accessdate=2009-02-10 |publisher=Movies Online |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104132905/http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_12524.html |archivedate=2009-01-04 }}</ref>\n\n===Further career===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Julie Kavner - This is my life.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Kavner's portrayal of Dottie Ingels in ''[[This Is My Life (1992 film)|This Is My Life]]'' was her first leading role in a feature film.]] -->\nMany of Kavner's roles have been described by ''New York Times'' writer Hilary de Vries as a \"woman who is supportive, sympathetic, or self-effacingly funny\".<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner grew to despise playing such roles, saying \"If it smacks of Brenda Morgenstern, I won't take the job.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/> She had a supporting role as Eleanor Costello, a nurse who befriends [[Robin Williams]]' character in the [[Academy Award]] nominated film ''[[Awakenings]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Awakenings |url=http://www.variety.com/profiles/Film/main/24664/Awakenings.html?dataSet=1 |work=Variety |accessdate=2009-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724205645/http://www.variety.com/profiles/Film/main/24664/Awakenings.html?dataSet=1 |archivedate=July 24, 2009 }}</ref> Kavner interviewed several nurses in preparation for the role, and [[Penny Marshall]], the director of the film, described Kavner as \"a low-maintenance actor [...] You never have to worry about giving [her] back-story for her characters.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/> In 1992, Kavner starred in ''[[This Is My Life (1992 film)|This Is My Life]]'', her first leading role in a feature film. Kavner played Dottie Ingels, an aspiring [[stand-up comedian]] who starts neglecting her family when her career begins to take off. Kavner described Dottie as \"really selfish\" but admitted, \"I liked the role for that very reason.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/> Kavner had been asked to play a character with a smaller role in the film, but [[Joe Roth]], at the time the chairman of [[20th Century Fox]], suggested that they cast a lesser known actress in the lead role.<ref name=\"darling\"/> [[Nora Ephron]], the writer of ''This Is My Life'', said Kavner \"has so little vanity that it is almost shocking. Not only does she have no demands as an actress - 'How big is my trailer, what's in my refrigerator?' - but she will do anything for the character if it makes sense to her.\"<ref name=\"darling\"/>\n\nKavner has frequently appeared in [[Woody Allen]] films, having roles in ''Hannah and Her Sisters'' (1986), ''[[Radio Days]]'' (1987), ''[[New York Stories]]'' (1989), ''[[Alice (1990 film)|Alice]]'' (1990), ''[[Shadows and Fog]]'' (1991), the television movie ''[[Don't Drink the Water (1994 film)|Don't Drink the Water]]'' (1994)<ref name=\"FoxFlash\"/> and ''[[Deconstructing Harry]]'' (1997).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117329532?refcatid=31|title=Deconstructing Harry|author=Stratton, David|date=1997-09-07|accessdate=2009-02-13|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> Allen described her as \"a naturally funny person. When she does a scene, you listen to her and look at her, and the prism through which it's all filtered is funny.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=The choicest of voices |author=Diamond, Jamie|work=[[Calgary Herald]]|date=1991-01-19}}</ref> Kavner believes he is \"a true filmmaker, one that has something to say, continually experimenting on different themes within his own film-making\", adding that \"anything [Allen] ever does, I always want to do, [...] I don't even have to read it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=Julie Kavner would follow Woody anywhere, even to the difficult medium of TV| work=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]|date=1994-12-17}}</ref>\n\nShe has done voice-over work in films such as ''[[The Lion King 1\u00bd]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=The Lion King 1\u00bd|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117923053?refCatId=1023|work=Variety|author=Leydon, Joe|date=2004-02-11}}</ref> ''[[Dr. Dolittle (1998 film)|Dr. Dolittle]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117477646?refcatid=31|title=Dr. Dolittle|author=Klady, Leonard|work=Variety|date=1998-06-24|accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref> and an uncredited role as an announcer in ''[[A Walk on the Moon]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117491901?refcatid=31|title=A Walk on the Moon|author=Lovell, Glenn|date=1999-03-09|accessdate=2009-02-13|work=Variety}}</ref> Her most recent live-action film was a role of the mother of [[Adam Sandler]]'s character in ''[[Click (2006 film)|Click]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Man-Child Who Has His World Under Control in 'Click'|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2006/06/23/movies/23clic.html|author=Dargis, Manohla|date=2006-06-23|accessdate=2009-02-13|work=The New York Times}}</ref> She also worked with Tracey Ullman in the HBO sketch comedy series ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]''.<ref name=\"FoxFlash\">{{cite web|title=Julie Kavner |url=http://www.foxflash.com/div.php/main/page?aID=1z2z2z175z13z4&bioid=1672 |publisher=FoxFlash |accessdate=2009-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929001926/http://www.foxflash.com/div.php/main/page?aID=1z2z2z175z13z4&bioid=1672 |archivedate=2011-09-29 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKavner leads a private, \"nearly reclusive\" life, \"discreet and guarded beyond the usual reticent star routine\".<ref name=\"darling\"/> She rarely makes public appearances and refuses to allow herself to be photographed at work, especially in the studio while doing ''The Simpsons''.<ref name=\"Winding\"/> Her partner is retired producer [[David Davis (TV producer)|David Davis]]; they have lived together since 1976.<ref name=\"Boston\"/><ref name=\"Winding\"/> In 1983, it was reported in ''[[Current Biography]]'' that Kavner is an avid athlete and a [[Pescetarianism|pescatarian]].<ref>''[[Current Biography Yearbook]], Volume 53''. (1992). H. W. Wilson Co. p. 318. \"Largely indifferent to food, Kavner generally follows a vegetarian diet, although she occasionally eats fish.\"</ref> In a 1992 interview with ''The New York Times'', Kavner said she was considering retiring, \"except for doing three days a year for Woody [Allen]\", but felt that if she did retire, she would receive a script she wanted \"to do more than life itself\".<ref name=\"darling\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[National Lampoon's Movie Madness]]''\n| Mrs. Falcone\n| \n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Bad Medicine (film)|Bad Medicine]]''\n| Cookie Katz\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Hannah and He